nce |url=https://archive.org/details/americanscriptur00paul |url-access=registration |location=New York, NY |publisher=Vintage Books |isbn=978-0679779087 |author-link=Pauline Maier |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mayville |first=Luke |title=John Adams and the Fear of American Oligarchy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tIn8CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11#v=onepage |date=2016 |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-14008-8369-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=McDonald |first=Forrest |date=1974 |title=The Presidency of George Washington |series=American Presidency |url=https://archive.org/details/presidencyofgeo000mcdo |url-access=registration |location=Lawrence, KS |publisher=University Press of Kansas |isbn=978-07006-0359-6 |author-link=Forrest McDonald |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Miller |first=Nathan |title=The U.S. Navy: A History, Third Edition |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PZZWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&dq=naval+power+adams+navy+miller#v=onepage&q=naval%2520power%2520adams%2520navy%2520miller |date=1997 |location=Annapolis, MD |publisher=Naval Institute Press |isbn=978-16125-1892-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Moore |first=George |date=1866 |title=Notes on the history of slavery in Massachusetts |url=https://archive.org/details/notesonhistorys01moorgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/notesonhistorys01moorgoog/page/n211 201] |location=New York, NY |publisher=D. Appleton & Co. |oclc=419266287 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Pollard |first=Edward A. |date=1862 |title=The First Year of the War |url=https://archive.org/details/firstyearofwar00poll |location=Richmond, VA |publisher=West & Johnson |author-link=Edward A. Pollard |oclc=79953002 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rossiter |first=Clinton |date=1955 |title=Conservatism in America |url=https://archive.org/details/conservatisminam00ross |url-access=registration |location=New York, NY |publisher=Knopf |author-link=Clinton Rossiter |oclc=440025153 |ref=harv}}\n* Scherr, Arthur (2018). ''John Adams, Slavery, and Race: Ideas, Politics, and Diplomacy in an Age of Crisis.'' Santa Barbara, CA: Praeger.\n* {{cite book |last=Shafer |first=Ronald G. |date=2016 |title=Carnival Campaign: How the Rollicking 1840 Campaign of \"Tippecanoe and Tyler Too\" Changed Presidential Politics Forever |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Carnival_Campaign.html?id=SAxmDAAAQBAJ |location=Chicago, IL |publisher=Chicago, Review Press |isbn=978-16137-3543-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=C. Bradley |date=1998 |title=John Adams and the Spirit of Liberty |url=https://archive.org/details/johnadamsspirito00thom |url-access=registration |location=Lawrence, KS |publisher=University Press of Kansas |isbn=978-07006-0915-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wiencek |first=Henry |date=2004 |title=An Imperfect God: George Washington, His Slaves, and the Creation of America |url=https://archive.org/details/imperfectgodgeor00wien_0 |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/imperfectgodgeor00wien_0/page/215 215] |location=Waterville, ME |publisher=Thorndike Press |isbn=978-07862-6129-1 |author-link=Henry Wiencek |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wood |first=Gordon S. |year=2006 |title=Revolutionary Characters: What Made the Founders Different |url=https://archive.org/details/revolutionarycha00gord |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/revolutionarycha00gord/page/54 54] |location=London, UK |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-1594200939 |author-link=Gordon S. Wood |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Gordon S. |last=Wood |date=2009 |title=Empire of Liberty: A history of the Early Republic, 1789\u20131815 |url=https://archive.org/details/empireoflibertyh00wood |url-access=registration |location=Oxford, UK |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-01997-4109-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wood |first=Gordon S. |year=2017 |title=Friends Divided: John Adams and Thomas Jefferson |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/556888/friends-divided-by-gordon-s-wood/9780735224735/ |location=New York, US |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0735224735 |author-link=Gordon S. Wood |ref=harv}}\n\n====Primary sources====\n* {{cite book |last1=Adams |first1=John |last2=Adams |first2=Charles Francis |date=1851 |title=The Works of John Adams, Second President of the United States: Autobiography, continued. Diary. Essays and controversial papers of the Revolution |volume=3 |series=The Works of John Adams, Second President of the United States |publisher=Little, Brown |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lWcsAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA392 |author-link2=Charles Francis Adams Sr. |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |editor-last=Biddle |editor-first=Alexander |title=Old Family Letters |url=https://archive.org/details/oldfamilyletter00rushgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/oldfamilyletter00rushgoog/page/n44 38] |date=1892 |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=Press of J.B. Lippincott Company |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |editor-last=Carey |editor-first=George Wescott |title=The Political Writings of John Adams |date=2001 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Gateway Editions}}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |editor-last=Diggins |editor-first=John Patrick |date=2004 |title=The Portable John Adams |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWdGUN6KPCcC&pg=PA466 |location=London, UK |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-01424-3778-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |editor-first=George A. Jr. |editor-last=Peek |date=1954 |title=The Political Writings of John Adams: Representative Selections |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5jrvsRgk5vwC&pg=PR17 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Liberal Arts Press |oclc=52727656 |ref=harv|isbn=978-0872206991 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |last2=Rush |first2=Benjamin |editor-last1=Schutz |editor-first1=John A. |editor-last2=Adair |editor-first2=Douglass |date=1966 |title=Spur of Fame, The Dialogues of John Adams and Benjamin Rush, 1805\u20131813 |url=https://archive.org/details/spuroffamedialog0000adam |url-access=registration |location=Santa Marino, CA |publisher=Huntington Library |isbn=978-08659-7287-2}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Adams |first1=John |last2=Tudor |first2=WIlliam |date=1819 |title=Novanglus, and Massachusettensis: Or, Political Essays, Published in the Years 1774 and 1775, on the Principal Points of Controversy, Between Great Britain and Her Colonies |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Hews & Gloss |url=https://archive.org/details/novanglusmassach00adams |author-link2=William Tudor |oclc=33610833}}\n* {{cite book |last=Adams |first=John |editor-last1=Wroth |editor-first1=L. Kinvin |editor-last2=Zobel |editor-first2=Hiller B. |title=The Legal Papers of John Adams |url=http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674522503 |date=1965 |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-06745-2250-3}}\n* Butterfield, L. H. et al., eds., ''The Adams Papers'' (1961\u2013 ). Multivolume letterpress edition of all letters to and from major members of the Adams family, plus their diaries; still incomplete. {{cite web|url=http://www.masshist.org/adams_editorial |title=The Adams Family Papers Editorial Project |publisher=Masshist.org |access-date=March 2, 2010}}\n* Butterfield, L. H., ed. [http://www.hup.harvard.edu/results-list.php?collection=1165 ''Adams Family Correspondence.''] Cambridge: Harvard University Press\n* {{cite book |editor=Cappon, Lester J. |title=The Adams-Jefferson Letters: The Complete Correspondence Between Thomas Jefferson and Abigail and John Adams |year=1959 |isbn=978-0807842300 |location=Chapel Hill, NC |publisher=The University of North Carolina Press}}\n* {{cite book |editor-link=Michael Foot |editor-last=Foot |editor-first=Michael |editor2-link=Isaac Kramnick |editor2-last=Kramnick |editor2-first=Isaac |date=1987 |title=The Thomas Paine Reader |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Thomas_Paine_Reader.html?id=GDRt70vGw9YC |publisher=Penguin Classics |isbn=978-01404-4496-4 |ref=harv}}\n* Hogan, Margaret; Taylor, C. James, eds. (2007). [http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674057050 ''My Dearest Friend: Letters of Abigail and John Adams.''] Cambridge: Harvard University Press.\n* {{cite book  |editor-last=Richardson |editor-first=James Daniel |date=1897 |title=A Compilation of the Messages and Papers of the Presidents |volume=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Compilation_of_the_Messages_and_Papers.html?id=EUMPAAAAYAAJ |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Harvard University |oclc=3144460227}}\n* Taylor, Robert J. et al., eds. [http://www.hup.harvard.edu/results-list.php?collection=1340 ''Papers of John Adams.''] Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{main|Bibliography of John Adams}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|en-John_Adams-article.ogg|2019-02-23}}\n* [https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/presidents/adams/ John Adams: A Resource Guide] at the [[Library of Congress]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080727101213/http://johnadamslibrary.org/ The John Adams Library] at the [[Boston Public Library]]\n* [http://www.masshist.org/digitaladams/archive/ Adams Family Papers: An Electronic Archive] at the [[Massachusetts Historical Society]]\n* [https://founders.archives.gov/about/Adams The Adams Papers], subset of [https://founders.archives.gov/ Founders Online] from the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]\n* [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/subject_menus/adamspap.asp John Adams Papers] at the [[Avalon Project]]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=4660}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John Adams}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=356}}\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?121951-1/life-portrait-john-adams \"Life Portrait of John Adams\"], from [[C-SPAN]]'s ''[[American Presidents: Life Portraits]]'', March 22, 1999\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-new|office|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to the United Kingdom|United States Minister to Great Britain]]|years=1785\u20131788}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Pinckney]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to the Netherlands|United States Minister to the Netherlands]]|years=1782\u20131788}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles W. F. Dumas]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice President of the United States]]|years=1789\u20131797}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Thomas Jefferson]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Washington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the United States]]|years=1797\u20131801}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|rows=2|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Federalist Party|Federalist]] nominee for Vice President of the United States|years=[[1792 United States presidential election|1792]]\u00b9\u00b2}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Pinckney]]\u00b2}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Federalist Party|Federalist]] nominee for President of the United States|years=[[1796 United States presidential election|1796]], [[1800 United States presidential election|1800]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles Cotesworth Pinckney]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Washington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Oldest living President of the United States]]|years=1799\u20131826}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Madison]]}}\n{{s-ref|While Adams won the vice presidency in [[1788\u201389 United States presidential election|1789]] as well, he was not the candidate of the Federalist Party, which had not yet formed.|Technically, Adams was a presidential candidate in 1792 and Pinckney was a presidential candidate in 1796. Prior to the passage of the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Twelfth Amendment]] in 1804, each presidential elector could cast two ballots; the highest vote-getter would become president and the runner-up would become vice president. Thus, in 1792, with [[George Washington]] as the prohibitive favorite for president, the Federalist party fielded Adams as a presidential candidate, with the intention that he be elected to the vice presidency. Similarly, in 1796 and 1800, the Federalist party fielded two candidates, Adams and Thomas Pinckney, in 1796 and Adams and [[Charles Cotesworth Pinckney|Charles Pinckney]] in 1800, with the intention that Adams be elected president and Pinckney be elected vice president.}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to John Adams\n|list=\n{{USDecOfIndSig}}\n{{US Presidents}}\n{{US Vice Presidents}}\n{{Federalist Party}}\n{{Unsuccessful major party pres candidates}}\n{{Age of Enlightenment}}\n{{US Ambassadors to the UK}}\n{{US Ambassadors to the Netherlands}}\n{{J Adams cabinet}}\n{{Hall of Fame for Great Americans}}\n{{John Quincy Adams}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|American Revolutionary War|United States|Politics|Law}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, John}}\n[[Category:John Adams| ]]\n[[Category:1735 births]]\n[[Category:1826 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:18th-century Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Washington administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1789 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1792 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1796 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1800 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Signers of the United States Declaration of Independence]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Members of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Continental Congressmen from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:18th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Federalists]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Braintree, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Fathers of Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Adams political family]]\n[[Category:Hall of Fame for Great Americans inductees]]\n[[Category:People of the Quasi-War]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1789\u20131849)]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts lawyers]]\n[[Category:American lawyers admitted to the practice of law by reading law]]\n[[Category:18th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Antiquarian Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n[[Category:American tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:18th-century Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:18th-century Unitarians]]\n[[Category:19th-century Unitarians]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Burials in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Adams"}
{"title_page": "Wacken Open Air", "text_new": "{{short description|German heavy metal music festival}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox music festival |\n  | music_festival_name = Wacken Open Air\n  | image = Festivalgel\u00e4nde - 2017215225222 2017-08-03 Wacken - Sven - 1D X MK II - 1539 - B70I9471.jpg\n  | caption = The burning skull is the official symbol for Wacken Open Air\n  | location = [[Wacken, Schleswig-Holstein|Wacken]], Germany\n  | years_active = 1990\u2013present\n  | genre = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]}}\n  | website = [https://www.wacken.com/en/ www.wacken.com]\n}}\n{{Listen\n|filename=We are the metalheads.ogg\n|title=We Are the Metalheads (2009)\n|description=The official Wacken Hymn, performed by [[Doro (musician)|Doro]] and Skyline.\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n'''Wacken Open Air''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|n}}, stylised '''W:O:A''') is a [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] [[music festival]], held annually since 1990 on the first weekend of August in the town of [[Wacken, Schleswig-Holstein|Wacken]] in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. Almost all styles of [[hard rock]] and metal are represented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://disctopia.de/live-and-ontour/metal-festivals-in-deutschland-osterreich-schweiz/|title=Metal Festival Landkarte 2015 f\u00fcr Deutschland & \u00d6sterreich {{!}} Disctopia Metal Webzine|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> It is now one of the largest heavy metal festivals in the world and one of the largest open-air festivals in Germany. Between 2011\u20132018, the number of attendees was around 85,000, 75,000 of whom were paying visitors. In 2020, the festival is scheduled to take place from 30 July to 1 August.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nThe idea for Wacken Open Air was conceived in 1989 when Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner visited a restaurant together. Both lived in Wacken and were friends, Jensen played the electric bass with [[Rock music|Rock]] cover band Skyline. From its beginnings until 1992, the band was composed of Ines Jeske from [[Vaale]] (vocals), Thomas Jensen from Wacken (bass), Peter Huhn from Wacken (electric guitar), Dennis Harman from [[Itzehoe]] (keyboard), and Andreas G\u00f6ser from Wacken (drums). Skyline was one of the first regional Metal and Rock [[cover band]]s at that time. The band was regionally known, working its way from appearances in village pubs and gigs at biker meetings up to an appearance as supporting band of \"[[Extrabreit]]\". H\u00fcbner was a disc jockey with a focus on Rock music and Heavy Metal. Jensen and H\u00fcbner developed the idea to organise an [[open-air concert]] in a gravel pit in Wacken and persuaded Skyline drummer Andreas G\u00f6ser and J\u00f6rg Jensen, Thomas Jensen's brother, to help make it happen. Until then, the pit had already served as a meeting venue for up to 3,000 members of biker club 'No Mercys', it was therefore perfectly suited for their plans and also presented an opportunity to attract motorcycle fans. From the beginning, it was clear that the focus of the event would be on Rock and Metal and that, in contrast to other single-day festivals such as [[Monsters of Rock]] or Super Rock in [[Mannheim]], there would also be camping grounds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=18\u201319}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|date=Spring 2013|title=Das W:O:A \u2013 Die Story in Zeitraffer|url=|journal=Wacken inside|volume=|pages=16\u201319|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Early years and initial development ===\n[[File:Wacken Promotion 1990.jpg|thumb|Advertisement for Wacken Open Air in 1990]]\nThe first two-day festival took place in the gravel pit on 24 and 25 August 1990 and barely had 800 visitors. The performing bands all hailed from Germany, and apart from Skyline, bands like 5th Avenue, Motoslug, Sacred Season, Axe 'n Sex, and Wizzard played. The first festivals were organised privately, with the technology being built on a trailer borrowed from a local trucking company and the stage being a DIY construction.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt.|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=19\u201322}}</ref>\n\nIn subsequent years, too, most of the tasks were carried out by the small team. Until August 1994, for example, ticket orders were organised privately by Andy G\u00f6ser's mother Regina G\u00f6ser and security duties were performed by friendly motorcycle clubs up until 1996.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=22\u201324}}</ref> In 1991, the number of visitors increased to 1.300,<ref name=\":2\" /> and with Skyline returning, Bon Scott, an [[AC/DC]] cover band from [[Hamburg]], Gypsy Kyss, Kilgore, Life Artist, Ruby Red, and Shanghai'd Guts joined them on stage for an all-regional roster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-history/history/woa-1991/bands/|title=Billing 1991|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> That same year, the iconic skull logo was designed by Mark Ramsauer after the basic shape had been determined by Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/schleswig-holstein/woa-2019-wikipedia-fakt-oder-fiktion-wacken-gruender-machen-faktencheck-id24948137.html|title=WOA 2019: Wikipedia Fakt oder Fiktion: Wacken-Gr\u00fcnder machen Faktencheck|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The cow skull refers to the venue, a meadow for cows, and to Jensen and H\u00fcbner as \"boys from the village\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockhard.de/megazine/heftarchiv/online-megazine/kolumne/25-jahre-wacken.html|title=25 Jahre Wacken|last=Eckhorst|first=Tim|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the programme changed to include internationally renowned bands such as [[Blind Guardian]] and [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] for the first time,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=24\u201326}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> and the number of bands rose to 26, listing bands from [[Sweden]], the [[United States|USA]], [[Ireland]], and [[Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-history/history/woa-1992/1/|title=Billing 1992|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The organisers used a professional stage with lighting and PA for the first time and were able to win cigarette brand Prince Denmark as a sponsor.<ref name=\":3\" /> That year, the Party Stage was set up in the DJ tent next to the main stage, where cover bands and fun projects were to perform exclusively. The additional post-concert costs for garbage disposal on the campground, where 2,500 paying guests and many more were present and celebrated, as well as the significantly oversized security, among other things, meant that the organisers recorded a loss of around 25,000 D-Mark that year.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWith the reunion of the band [[Fates Warning]] at the festival in 1993, Wacken Open Air had a special feature and also made a name for itself in the following years with unusual band constellations and reunions. At the same time, [[Doro (musician)|Doro Pesch]] and other well-known bands made for interesting appearances, which resulted in a new record attendance of 3,500 paying customers. Simultaneously, the team tried their hand at concert organisation and, under the moniker Stone Castle Promotion, held a [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] concert for 2,000 people in Flensburg which, unfortunately, could not cover its promotional costs. A show with [[Dio (band)|Dio]]/Freak of Nature became a disaster with only 167 tickets sold, and together with the Open Air, which again recorded a minus, the organisers incurred debts of around 350,000 D-Mark. As a result, J\u00f6rg Jensen and Andreas G\u00f6ser left the team; Holger H\u00fcbner and Thomas Jensen remained, as did J\u00f6rn-Ulf Goesmann for another two years, continuing to run the Wacken Open Air despite the debts for which their parents had provided guarantees. During the same year, Thomas Jensen's mother died and Holger H\u00fcbner had a serious accident \u2013 the year went down in Wacken history as the \"year of the plague\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=27\u201330}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn its fifth anniversary in 1994, the financial situation stabilised and the festival finally broke even. The line-up remained professional and featured many internationally known bands from the [[Metal scene]]. A total of 4,500 tickets were sold; on top of that, due to the rising costs of garbage disposal, tickets for the camping grounds had to be purchased separately, and pre-orders were rewarded with a free T-shirt.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=30\u201331}}</ref> Also in 1995, income and expenses evened out thanks to the commitment of bands such as [[Tiamat (band)|Tiamat]], [[D.A.D. (band)|D-A-D]], the [[Pretty Maids]], and [[Angra (band)|Angra]]. But even with roughly 5,000 attendees, the festival didn't turn a profit.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=32\u201333}}</ref> However, for the first time, national media became aware of Wacken Open Air, especially [[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] magazine, as well as the newly founded TV station [[VIVA Germany|VIVA]] with its Heavy Metal programme ''Metalla''.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== First achievements and growth ===\nTicket sales for the 1996 festival again started sluggishly, despite a headliner like [[Kreator]] and numerous internationally renowned bands such as [[The Exploited]], [[Gorefest]], and [[Crematory (band)|Crematory]]. Management tried to prevent another loss by securing more acts and finally managed to get [[B\u00f6hse Onkelz]] to perform. The engagement of the controversial band also led to criticism, and some bands cancelled their gig in Wacken that year. Cologne band [[Brings]] called off their gig on short notice and offered to refund their fans\u2019 ticket prices.<ref>\u201eNews\" from Hamburger Abendblatt, 6. August 1996, p. 12</ref>\n\nAs a result of many visitors flooding the village in 1996, the inhabitants of Wacken voiced their concern over an event of this size being held in the local gravel pit. Uwe Trede offered to relocate the festival site to his own property and the areas previously used as campgrounds and took care of the acquisition of additional land. The organisational team grew to include Thomas Hess as production manager, who had previously been active as tour manager for Die B\u00f6hsen Onkelz, as well as Sheree Hesse for catering to the artists and VIPs. With the W.E.T.-Stage, a third stage was set up in 1997. The \"Wacken Evolution Tent\" was to be made available primarily to newcomers and bands without record deals. That year, the number of visitors reached 10,000 for the first time, with [[Rockbitch]]'s erotic stage show causing a scene.<ref>Andreas Sch\u00f6we: ''Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt''. H\u00f6fen 2012, p. 35\u201337</ref>\n\n=== Further development of the festival ===\n[[File:WackenOpenAir.jpg|thumb|W:O:A 2005 was attended by 40,000 people]]\nOver the years, the size of Wacken Open Air has grown continuously, and now dozens of bands and tens of thousands of visitors flock to the festival. Even though the organisers said in 2006 that 62,500 visitors were \"the limit of what is possible\",<ref>press conference in 2006 (source needed)</ref> changes were made to the structure of the festival grounds the following year by allocating a larger area to the \"Party Stage\". In addition, tickets could no longer be purchased directly on the festival grounds to reduce the number of spontaneous or ticketless visitors. In 2007 and 2008, the festival had already sold out as a result of advance ticket sales; for W:O:A 2009, tickets had even sold out by the end of 2008. The tickets for 2010, too, sold out months in advance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2010/main-news/news/ansicht/article/wahnsinn-wacken-im-5-jahr-hintereinander-ausverkauft-resttickets-bei-unseren-buspartnern-erhaeltli/|title=News on wacken.com|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhile the festival originally only lasted two days, the performances have been lasting from Thursday to Saturday, i.e. three days, for some years. Thursday became a \"Night to Remember\", with mainly \"classical\" Heavy Metal bands appearing, such as the [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]] in 2006. On the actual Party Stage, younger and more modern bands play as a contrast to the \"Night to Remember\". In addition, the event is accompanied by a rich complementary programme; in addition to a merchant area \u2013 obligatory for music festivals \u2013 a beer garden has been operating since 2000, in which the [[Wacken Firefighters]]' marching band opens the festival before its official start. On Thursday in 2007, the \"Hellfest Stage\" was initiated. Since 2009, there has been a \"Medieval Stage\", where mainly [[Middle Ages|Medieval]] and [[Folk metal|Folk Metal]] bands play.\n\nThe fact that many well-known bands, including the Scorpions, [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]], [[Twisted Sister]], [[Dimmu Borgir]], [[Slayer]], and [[Helloween]], have recorded live [[DVD]]s at Wacken, shows how esteemed the Open Air has since become. Ahead of their farewell tour in 2004, Die B\u00f6hsen Onkelz also performed an extended set at W:O:A.\n\nSince 2002, the so-called \"Metal Train\" has been travelling from [[Z\u00fcrich|Zurich]] to Wacken and back before and after the festival to bring fans to the Northern German village and provide a matching entertainment programme. Bus tours from [[Scandinavia]]n countries, especially [[Sweden]], but also from [[Austria]], are organised each year and used by several hundred fans.\n\nThe \"W:O:A Soccercup\" has been taking place annually since 2002. This football tournament, which started with nine teams and takes place on Wednesdays, has grown over the years and has been held in World Cup mode with 32 teams since 2007 (a one-off event in 2011 featured 36 teams). The international teams register in advance and are composed of festival visitors. For the tournament's 15th anniversary in 2016, a band was featured and took part for the first time: [[Serum 114]] formed a team with several fans and were able to win the tournament. Although it is meant to be a fun tournament, in which creative outfits and names take precedence over athletic performance, the award ceremony after the tournament has been held on one of the stages since 2013 and prices can be won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808210920/http://neu.woa-soccercup.de/|title=W:O:A Soccercup|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the \"Full Metal Church\" took place in Wacken for the first time. Marking the local church's 150th anniversary, the team, together with the parish, organised a concert by the band [[Faun (band)|Faun]], which was framed by two readings and sermons by \"[[Volxbibel]]\" author Martin Dreyer. Both the concert and the services were completely overcrowded by festival visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_kAR2EWlgk|title=Full Metal Church|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Present ===\n[[File:Alice Cooper - Wacken Open Air 2017 03.jpg|left|thumb|Alice Cooper at Wacken Open Air 2017]]\nThe festival is one of the Metal scene's highlights of the year. Nowadays, about a third of the visitors, some of whom arrive quite some time before the official start of the festival, and the majority of the bands come from abroad. According to the organisers, 2018 saw visitors from more than 80 nations attending the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/die-ersten-bands-fuer-das-wacken-open-air-2019/|title=Die ersten Bands f\u00fcr das Wacken Open Air 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe number of participants increased to 75,000 in 2008 and included 65,000 paying guests. In 2008, the festival sold out twice ( W:O:A 2008 in spring and W:O:A 2009 on 31 December 2008).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2010/main-news/news/archiv/archiv-single/article/wahnsinn-wacken-sold-out/|title=Wahnsinn Wacken \u2013 Sold Out!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs is common with festivals of this size, Wacken Open Air received criticism for its hygienic conditions, prices, security personnel, as well as for the overcrowding and commercial orientation of the event. These points of criticism were addressed by making further substantial investments in the festival's fixed and mobile infrastructure. In 2008, the organisers also contributed 1,000,000 Euros to the expansion of Wacken's local outdoor swimming pool in order to make the festival even more attractive to the residents and visitors of the town.<ref>Information provided by mayor Axel Kunkel</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the festival has been running an [[Internet radio|online radio]] station called [[Wacken Radio]], which broadcasts Metal music around the clock. It is being produced in cooperation with [[RauteMusik.FM|RauteMusik]] as of February 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rautemusik.fm/wackenradio/|title=Wacken Metal Radio \u2013 Heavy Metal Radio \u2013 Metalcore & Grindcore \u2013 RauteMusik.FM Internetradio|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Wikipedians at WOA 2011.JPG|thumb|Attendees at Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nFor the 23rd edition of Wacken Open Air, the sale of an \"X-Mas Package\" started on Monday, 8 August 2011, shortly after the end of that year's festival, and was sold out within 45 minutes. The event sold out ten times in a row between 2006 and 2015. Tickets for Wacken Open Air 2015 sold out after just 12 hours on 4 August 2014 \u2013 just a few hours after the end of W:O:A 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-tickets-shop/tickets/-/|title=Das W:O:A ist zum zehnten Mal SOLD OUT!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The X-Mas Tickets for W:O:A 2016, which cost 10 Euros less and whose buyers were entitled to a free T-shirt, were completely sold out only 20 minutes after the start of pre-sales. Booking office Metaltix\u2019 servers were highly busy. In the minutes before the start of the pre-sale, the pages were no longer accessible; after that, [[Network traffic|data traffic]] had to be limited by wait lists.\n\nPrices for the festival have risen and are currently at a level similar to other major Rock festivals, such as [[Rock am Ring and Rock im Park|Rock am Ring]] and [[Hurricane Festival]]. After several years of success in which the festival sold out within hours, the first 60,000 tickets for the 2017 festival were sold in mid-2016. 55,000 tickets were sold within the first hour. By the end of April 2017, the festival was almost sold out except for a few remaining tickets. The price for the festival ticket was 220 Euros, but there was no fee for early arrival campers, who often set up their elaborately designed accommodations before the festival begins \u2013 partly to get the best spots near the festival grounds. In addition, all toilets and showers were free in 2017.\n\nThe festival sold out within a few days each in 2014\u20132016. However, the last tickets for the 2017 festival were sold after 309 days, a mere 2 months before the start of the festival, even though only 10,000 tickets remained after the first day of sales. This was a matter of speculation at first, and reasons such as the changed security situation or the price development were taken into account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/themen/wacken-open-air/holger-huebner-darum-ist-das-woa-2017-noch-nicht-ausverkauft-id14616776.html|title=Holger H\u00fcbner: Darum ist das WOA 2017 noch nicht ausverkauft|last=|first=|date=20 August 2016|website=SHZ.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Regardless of that, the festival sold out for the 13th time in a row in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/themen/wacken-open-air/woa-ist-ausverkauft-alle-75-000-tickets-sind-weg-id17048861.html|title=WOA ist ausverkauft \u2013 alle 75.000 Tickets sind weg|last=|first=|date=13 June 2017|website=SHZ.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2018 Thomas Hess, the festival's longtime production (and former security) director, passed away. He had joined festival management in 1996 as a former tour manager of B\u00f6hse Onkelz and was considered one of the most important leading figures for the festival, along with the remaining founders and the Trede family, who organise the camping areas and the camping supervisors as subcontractors. He made a significant contribution to the W:O:A being so well organised, peaceful and successful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/nachruf-thomas-hess/|title=Nachruf Thomas Hess|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nWacken Open Air 2018 was named the best major festival at the European Festival Awards 2018 and best festival at the Helga! Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/best-major-festival-das-woa-2018-gewinnt-bei-den-european-festival-awards/|title=Best Major Festival \u2013 das W:O:A 2018 gewinnt bei den European Festival Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> For W:O:A 2019, all 75,000 tickets were sold within the first four days of sales, making this the 14th time in a row that the festival completely sold out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/das-30-wacken-open-air-ist-ausverkauft/|title=Das 30. Wacken Open Air ist ausverkauft!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:Wacken 2011 Impression 05.JPG|thumb|Sanitary facilities on the camping grounds with illuminated \"sign of the horns\", Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nThe organisers of Wacken Open Air founded ''Stone Castle Rockpromotions'' in 1990 in order to organise the first festival. The name is derived from the direct translation of \"Steinburg\" from the district of [[Steinburg]], to which Wacken belongs.<ref name=\":1\" /> Stone Castle remained the company's name until 1996. Up until 2014, the headquarters were located in [[D\u00f6rpstedt|D\u00f6rpstedt (Schleswig-Flensburg district)]] and then moved to Wacken. The company's name has been ''ICS'' (International Concert Service) GmbH since 1999. The company owns the label ''Wacken Records'' and the [[Mail order|mailorder]] Metaltix, among others.\n\nA daily festival newspaper has been available since 2007, reporting on what's happening on the festival grounds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Metall macht Musik|last=Eckhorst|first=Tim|publisher=TheNextArt Verlag|year=2008|isbn=978-3-939400-18-9|location=|pages=83}}</ref> The Thursday edition is also included free of charge with all newspapers published by [[Schleswig-Holsteinischer Zeitungsverlag]].\n\nIn 2014, the online radio station RauteMusik took over production of the official Wacken radio. Wacken Radio has its own container on the festival grounds every year, where it reports live.\n\nUp until a few years ago, Wacken's official town signs were either replaced by plastic signs spelling Heavy Metal Town during W:O:A or bolted more tightly because they were often stolen as souvenirs. Some shops are now selling black cotton bags with the Wacken town sign on one side and the words \"This town sign I may keep\" on the other.\n\nAn action for exceeding the maximum noise limit, brought before the Administrative Court of Schleswig by residents of Wacken, ended in January 2013 with an out-of-court settlement. Now, if the average noise level of the festival exceeds 70&nbsp;dB, the organisers pay 1,000 Euros to the community, which donates the money to charitable causes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/musik-festival-wacken-darf-laut-bleiben-a-879534.html|title=Anwohner bes\u00e4nftigt: Wacken darf weiter rocken|last=|first=|date=|website=Spiegel Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nThe site covers more than 240 [[hectare]]s, which are divided by more than 45 kilometres of fence. The inner area, including the main stage, has a size of 43,000 [[square metre]]s. More than 1,300 toilets and almost 500 showers are available for the 75,000 paying attendees. 2,200 trucks with equipment are needed for the entire festival. Stage construction and dismantling usually take 7 days and 5 days respectively. For this, 75 trucks of stage equipment (1,000 tons), 10 trucks of sound equipment and 27 trucks of lighting equipment are used.<ref name=\":5\">W:O:A press kit 2018</ref>\n\nSince 2014, the [[Electricity|electric]] output has amounted to 12 megawatts, roughly matching the needs of a small town counting 70,000 inhabitants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wacken.shz.de/woa2014/|title=Wacken - 25 Jahre Metal-Mythos|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.saz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> In addition, 40 diesel-fuelled [[Emergency power system|emergency power generators]] are required. 25 electricians are responsible for the power supply.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n600,000 Euros were spent on the construction of sewage systems and the improvement of power supply on the festival grounds. At the same time, 700,000 Euros worth of drains were installed in front of the stages in order to improve the drainage of water masses during heavy rains. The main paths were also paved with 10&nbsp;km of mobile roads to facilitate access for rescue vehicles.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nA total of approximately 5,000 employees work for the festival, including 1,800 security staff members, 150 cleaners, 70 construction and dismantling assistants, as well as 400 police officers, 250 firefighters, 900 paramedics, and six emergency doctors.\n\nIn 2017, a beer pipeline measuring one kilometer to supply ten dispensing systems was used for the first time. At full capacity, this construction allowed for 10,000 litres of beer to be tapped within the hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/kultur/musik/wacken-open-air-2017-bier-pipeline-liefert-10000-liter-pro-stunde_aid-17915041|title=Wacken Open Air 2017: Bier-Pipeline liefert 10.000 Liter pro Stunde|last=|first=|date=|website=RP Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stages ===\n[[File:Nightwish - Wacken Open Air 2018-1769.jpg|thumb|Faster/Harder Stages at Wacken Open Air 2018]]\nWacken Open Air now boasts eight stages for musicians and accompanying entertainment. The most important ones are the Faster and the Harder Stage, which are designed as connected twin stages and have a shared sound and lighting system. Together with the slightly smaller Louder Stage, these two stages make up the Infield, or The Holy Ground. All three stages are also equipped with [[video wall]]s to allow visibility of the performers even from remote positions.\n\nUp until 2016, these three stages were called Black Stage, True Metal Stage, and Party Stage. After Wacken 2016, visitors were encouraged to suggest new names. From these suggestions, the best ideas were to be put up to a vote in a survey. Instead, however,\u00a0 the slogan \"Faster - Harder - Louder\" became the inspiration for the names and the three stages were renamed accordingly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/mehr-sound-und-neue-namen-die-buehnen-im-infield/|title=Mehr Sound und neue Namen \u2013 die B\u00fchnen im Infield!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo more twin stages, the W.E.T. Stage (Wacken Evolution Tent) and the Headbanger Stage, are located inside a big tent called Bullhead City Circus. The Metal Battle takes place on these stages on Wednesday and Thursday, followed by regular band appearances on the days after.\n\nWhile the large stages and tent stages are open to all genres, the remaining stages are dedicated to specific themes. The Wackinger Stage is located in the medieval area of the festival and is played primarily by bands from Folk, Pagan and Medieval genres, while the Wasteland Stage, which was established in 2014, is geared towards music with an apocalyptic touch. The Beergarden Stage is modelled after typical folk festival stages, but also accommodates permanent Wacken guests such as the Wacken Firefighters and [[Mambo Kurt]].\n\n=== Event area ===\n[[File:Wastelander \u2013 Wacken Open Air 2014 05.jpg|thumb|Wasteland \u2013 apocalypse at Wacken Open Air 2014]]\nWacken Open Air's event area is divided into several structurally separated sections. Since 2014, only one major security check is performed upon entering the grounds, after that, only the festival wristbands are checked.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/ein-vierteljahrhundert-wacken-open-air-ist-history/|title=Ein Vierteljahrhundert Wacken Open Air ist History!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpecial features of the W:O:A include the Wackinger area, which resembles a medieval market and contains specialty food and beverage stalls as well as the Wackinger Stage, where matching music is played. Various walking acts also entertain the audience. This area borders on the Wasteland designed by the [[Wasteland Warriors]], where a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] world and stage (Wastelandstage) styled in homage to the [[Mad Max (franchise)|Mad Max]]-franchise is set up.\n\nThe area in front of the main stages comprises both the [[Bavaria]]n [[beer garden]] and a large shopping mile called Metal Markt. There are also various food stalls, the Wacken Foundation Camp, ATMs, and the Movie Field, where Heavy Metal [[Documentary film|documentaries]] and [[feature film]]s are screened.\n\nThe most important stages, the focal point of the festival, are located in the so-called Infield, which can be reached only via the Center. In addition to these stages, it also hosts food and beverage stalls.\n\n=== Camping grounds ===\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde Wasteland - Wacken Open Air 2016-AL0321.jpg|thumb|Wasteland festival grounds at Wacken Open Air 2016]]\nAs Wacken Open Air only sells 3-day tickets, the majority of visitors spend the entire festival on-site. As a result, most of the more than 240 hectares of the festival site are designated camping areas. Camping opens on Monday and has been included in the ticket price since 2017. However, in the years before, an extra fee was charged for arrival before Wednesday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/infos-zum-vorverkauf-fuer-das-woa-2017/|title=Infos zum Vorverkauf f\u00fcr das W:O:A 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe campsite is equipped with showers, flushing toilets, [[portable toilet]]s, [[drinking fountain]]s, small supermarkets, food stalls, and information boards, and is continuously patrolled by the police, fire brigade, and security services. A garbage collection service collects full garbage bags on the premises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2015/main-news/news/news-suche/suche-ansicht/article/metal4nature-2014-9413/|title=Metal4nature|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor orientation, the individual sites called Campgrounds are marked with code letters. Campgrounds A and B are reserved for visitors arriving without a car, while Campgrounds Y and R are intended for campers and other heavy-duty vehicles. Y offers the possibility to rent entire caravans, tents or to get a power supply for your own [[Caravan (towed trailer)|caravan]]. At Campground U, large groups of 50 people or more can reserve a larger area free of charge.\n\nSince the large crowds lead to a bottleneck situation in terms of mobile service, some providers now set up portable [[base station]]s for [[GSM]], [[UMTS]], and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]+ during the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vodafone.de/featured/?vf_origin_url=music/wacken-nature-one-und-co-vodafone-ruestet-sein-netz-fuer-den-festivalsommer/|title=Wacken, Nature One und Co. \u2013 Vodafone r\u00fcstet sein Netz f\u00fcr den Festivalsommer|last=|first=|date=|website=vodafone.de|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical services ===\nA festival of this size needs capable medical services, which here are called the Wacken Rescue Squad. Every year, hundreds of helpers from various relief organisations from all over Germany arrive before the festival to prepare the medical camp and care for people in need during the event. The medical service is managed by the local [[German Red Cross|DRK]] association in [[Kaltenkirchen]].\n\nThe visiting and local relief organisations provide vehicles and material during the course of the festival. These include ambulances and radios for communication in particular. Due to the road conditions, quads and foot patrols are often used in Wacken, especially in the vicinity of the medical centre. In addition to the medical service, which counts approx. 270 people at peak times, the rescue service cooperation Schleswig-Holstein has more than ten emergency vehicles (ambulances and mobile intensive care units) on site while coordinating the overall [[emergency management]].\n\nIn 2013, around 3,300 people received medical care from approximately 500 paramedics.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20130804124442/http://www.ndr.de/unterhaltung/events/wacken/woa_2013/wacken2849.html|title=Wacken-Fans machen sich auf den Heimweg|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Crime and accidents ===\nDespite the size of the festival, no serious security problems have been encountered so far. Disputes among visitors are rare, and in 2011, a total of 20 reports of bodily injury was filed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studium.at/139030-wacken-2011-95000-fans-rockten-weltweit-groessten-heavy-metal-festival|title=Wacken 2011: 95.000 Fans rockten am weltweit gr\u00f6\u00dften Heavy Metal Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=studium.at|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The main problem consists of several hundred reported thefts each year. In 2011, police were able to arrest three gangs of thieves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/panorama/gesellschaft/heavy-metal-treffen-polizei-schnappt-drei-diebesbanden-in-wacken-a-778666.html|title=Heavy-Metal-Treffen: Polizei schnappt drei Diebesbanden in Wacken|last=|first=|date=|website=Spiegel Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> In comparison to other events of this scale, the festival is classified by police as secure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fr-online.de/panorama/wacken-open-air-2012-unfalltod-ueberschattet-wacken-bilanz,1472782,16811984.html|title=Unfalltod \u00fcberschattet Wacken-Bilanz|last=|first=|date=|website=Franfurter Rundschau online|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSo far there have been four deaths and some serious injuries:\n\n* In 2005, a heavily intoxicated 37-year-old crashed into an ambulance moving at walking pace and succumbed to his head injuries in the hospital. To support his family, organisers held a fundraising event; W:O:A 2006 honoured the deceased with a minute's silence.\n* In 2011, a rioting fan was overwhelmed by security guards in the village and died of [[Cardiac arrest|cardiovascular arrest]].\n* In 2012, a 22-year-old festival visitor went to sleep near a [[Electric generator|generator]] and breathed in its [[carbon monoxide]] fumes. He could not be revived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/panorama/welt/todesfall-bei-musik-festival-in-wacken-metal-fan-leblos-aufgefunden_aid_793853.html|title=Todesfall bei Musik-Festival in Wacken: Metal-Fan leblos aufgefunden|last=|first=|date=|website=Focus online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* In 2013, a 52-year-old visitor from Poland died of natural causes in his tent. That same year, a fan was seriously injured when the cartridge of his camping stove exploded for unknown reasons.<ref name=\":7\" />\n* In 2016, two men were injured when one of them set fire to illegal [[firecracker]]s and the other tried to stop him. Reports that one of the men's ears had been torn off turned out to be false.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/schleswig-holstein/boeller-explosion-in-wacken-feuerwehrmann-es-war-alles-ganz-anders-id14544331.html|title=B\u00f6ller-Explosion in Wacken \u2013 Feuerwehrmann: \"Es war alles ganz anders\"|last=|first=|date=|website=shz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* In 2017, a 16-year-old was seriously injured while trying to refill a [[Portable stove|camping stove]] with [[denatured alcohol]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kn-online.de/Nachrichten/Schleswig-Holstein/Verbrennungen-16-Jaehriger-beim-WOA-verletzt|title=16-J\u00e4hriger beim Wacken Open Air verletzt|last=|first=|date=1 August 2017|website=Kieler Nachrichten|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Commitment ==\n\n=== Metal Battle ===\n[[File:Metal Battle - 2017216154323 2017-08-04 Wacken - Sven - 5DS R - 0106 - 5DSR2534.jpg|thumb|The 2017 winners of Metal Battle, Mexican band Jet Jaguar]]\nW:O:A Metal Battle is an international band contest first held in 2004. During Metal Battle, newcomer bands compete against each other in national qualifiers and finals; the winner of each country then competes against the other finalists in the grand final at Wacken Open Air.\n\nAn international jury selects the competition's best bands. In earlier years, winners of the competition were offered a record deal, whereas nowadays, the five best bands receive cash or material prices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-battle.com/about/|title=Metal Battle|last=|first=|date=|website=Metal Battle|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Foundation ===\nThe [[Wacken Foundation]] was founded in 2009 by the festival's organisers and serves as a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|charitable foundation]]. Its objective is to support young bands from the Heavy Metal genre.\n\nSponsorship is granted to specific projects such as the production of a [[Compact disc|CD]] or the realisation of a tour. In addition, the Wacken Foundation provides information about its projects at many [[Europe]]an festivals each summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wacken-foundation.com/home/|title=Wacken Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=Wacken Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Since the 2017/2018 season, the Wacken Foundation's lettering can be found on the jerseys of German 3rd league club [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]. This was facilitated by jersey sponsors [[Heaven Shall Burn]], whose [[logo]] has been moved to the jersey's sleeve for this cause. Part of the proceeds from the jersey's sale is donated to the foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/ost-thueringen/carl-zeiss-jena-wacken-sponsor-trikotsponsor-100.html|title=Carl Zeiss Jena l\u00e4uft mit Wacken auf der Brust auf|last=|first=|date=|website=mdr.de|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Music Camp ===\n2014 saw Wacken Music Camp take place for the first time. One week after the festival ended, young people from all over Germany were invited to write and play their own songs under the guidance of professional musicians. They were accommodated in the so-called Kuhle, the site of the first Wacken Open Air.\n\n=== Blood donations ===\nThe organisers regularly call for [[blood donation]]s with the whole festival team. Blood is donated at the Itzehoe Clinic and the entire wing is decorated in W:O:A style, while Heavy Metal is blasted through the speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/lokales/norddeutsche-rundschau/wacken-metal-fans-lassen-sich-anzapfen-id6834671.html|title=Wacken: Metal-Fans lassen sich anzapfen|last=|first=|date=14 June 2014|website=shz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== DKMS typing campaign ===\nSince W:O:A 2014, visitors and musicians have been encouraged to have their [[bone marrow]] typed for donation by the [[DKMS|German Bone Marrow Donor Database]]. In 2014, 2,700 visitors took this opportunity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120607/http://www.dkms.de/de/content/wacken-und-die-dkms-%E2%80%93-laut-und-erfolgreich|title=Wacken und die DKMS \u2013 Laut und erfolgreich|last=|first=|date=|website=DKMS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stark gegen Krebs \u2013 Strong against cancer ===\nThe festival works with the organisers of the so-called Wattol\u00fcmpiade (\"mudflat Olympics\") in [[Brunsb\u00fcttel]] to promote the slogan Stark gegen Krebs (\"Strong against cancer\"). The festival's team helps out with logistics for the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2015/main-news/news/archiv/archiv-single/article/stark-gegen-krebs-kooperation-vom-wacken-open-air-mit-der-wattoluempiade-9322/|title=Stark gegen Krebs|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Network \u2013 W:O:A as a brand ==\n[[File:Wacken 2011 Impression 08.JPG|thumb|Tower with Wacken symbol, Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nIn addition to the festival itself, there are numerous other events planned and carried out by the organisers. A wide range of [[merchandising]] has also been developed over the years. In addition to T-shirts and a comprehensive range of CDs and DVDs, the festival also has accompanying [[print media]]. The ''W:O:A History Book'' contains the open-air's history up until 2005. The book Die Wahrheit \u00fcber Wacken (\"The truth about Wacken\", Oidium Verlag 2005, new edition published at Verlag Andreas Reiffer 2011) provides a more humorous account of the festival. It was written by satirist Till Burgw\u00e4chter in collaboration with comic artist Jan Oidium and is also available as an audio book comprising three CDs. The publication of a Metal cookbook shows how far merchandising has come. However, the mounting range of merchandising has led to growing criticism, as some consider it to be purely profit-oriented. The increasing coverage of the festival, especially in the wake of the documentary [[Full Metal Village]], is perceived by the traditional Metal scene as \"selling out\".\n\nIn 2005, Wacken Premium [[Pilsner]] was offered as the festival's \"own\" beer for the first time. It was produced in the Bavarian [[brewery]] Maximiliansbrauerei in [[Chieming]]. At W:O:A 2006 and 2007, the beer was available as well, this time produced in 0.5-litre bottles by the [[Flensburger Brauerei|Flensburger]] brewery. The large number of glass shards later forced the organisers to switch to 0.5-litre cans.\n\nAs a [[motto]], the phrase \"See you in Wacken - Rain or Shine\" has established itself alongside \"Faster, Harder, Louder\". Additionally, the festival features the sentence \"Louder Than Hell\" in its advertising.\n\n=== Full Metal Cruise ===\n[[Cruise ship|Cruises]] with Heavy Metal bands on board under the name [[Full Metal Cruise]] have been organised within Europe since 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamburg.de/kreuzfahrtschiffe/3500106/full-metal-cruise/|title=Full Metal Cruise: Heavy Metal auf hoher See|last=|first=|date=|website=Hamburg.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Hamburg Metal Dayz ===\nThe indoor festival [[Hamburg Metal Dayz]] takes place at the same time as the [[Reeperbahn]]-Festival and is considered a get-together for the scene. In addition to concerts, there are panels with musicians, managers, and other Metal experts, as well as workshops and a question and answer session with the W:O:A organisers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hh-mittendrin.de/2014/09/hamburg-metal-dayz-gepflegter-krach-in-der-markthalle/|title=Hamburg Metal Dayz \u2013 gepflegter Krach in der Markthalle|last=|first=|date=23 September 2014|website=hh-mittendrin.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Roadshow ===\n[[File:Grailknights \u2013 Wacken Roadshow 2014 01.jpg|thumb|[[Grailknights]] at Wacken Roadshow 2014]]\nFor the Wacken Roadshow, several bands tour Europe under the banner of Wacken Open Air. These concerts are meant to complement the warm-up parties organised in many places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-hammer.de/metal-hammer-praesentiert-woa-roadshow-2014-398382/|title=METAL HAMMER pr\u00e4sentiert: W:O:A Roadshow 2014|last=|first=|date=9 April 2014|website=Metal Hammer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Metal Monday ===\nIn the summer of 1990, Metal Monday took place for the first time at Knust in [[Hamburg]]. For five years, regional, national and international Metal bands like De la Cruz, 5th Avenue, and King K\u00f8ng played at Knust every Monday. After a break of almost 20 years, Metal Monday was revived by the Wacken Open Air organisers in 2014 in cooperation with the Knust, Seaside Touring, All Access, and Hamburg Konzerte. Metal, Rock, and Folkrock bands now perform once a month, following the motto \"three bands - small entrance fee\". In addition to regional bands, international newcomers are always invited.\n\n=== Zum Wackinger ===\n[[File:Martin Semmelrogge - Zum Wackinger - Wacken Winter Nights 2017 08.jpg|thumb|Reading with [[Martin Semmelrogge]] at Zum Wackinger 2017]]\nThe former country-style restaurant ''Zur Post'' in Wacken, built in 1919, has been the hub of the village and the surrounding communities for decades. It was here that bartenders Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner conceived the idea for today's Wacken Open Air. Today, it is used to accommodate staff and to serve other business purposes. A series of events called \"Zum Wackinger\" sees artists from music, comedy, and entertainment perform regularly. Since 2016, a two-day medieval feast with jugglers and bards takes place here.<ref>press kit ICS Network, ''Zum Wackinger'', September 2016 (p. 37)</ref>\n\n=== Metal Church ===\nThe Evangelical Lutheran Village Church in Wacken belongs to the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] congregation of the [[Evangelical Church in Germany|Evangelical Lutheran Church]] in [[Northern Germany]]. For Wacken Open Air and Wacken Winter Nights, it is turned into the ''Metal Church''. During said festivals, the ''Metal Service'' is held here and bands from the Folk and Medieval scene perform in the church.\n\n=== Wacken Winter Nights ===\n[[File:Dunkelsch\u00f6n - Metal Church - Wacken Winter Nights 2017 01.jpg|thumb|[[Dunkelsch\u00f6n]] at Metal Church during Wacken Winter Nights]]\nWacken Winter Nights (WWN), a three-day Folk and Medieval open-air festival, took place for the first time in February 2017 at temperatures of -2 to -6 degrees Celsius in Wacken. With over 3,500 attendees, the festival's first edition sold out several weeks in advance. Most of them spent the nights on the camping site. A second edition took place from 23 to 25 February 2018. Due to the construction on the previous year's campground, the overnight accommodations were relocated to the area that is also used for the regular Open Air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/wwn-2018-festival-abc-und-plaene-verfuegbar/|title=WWN 2018 Festival ABC und Pl\u00e4ne verf\u00fcgbar!|last=|first=|date=2 February 2018|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The walking distance, therefore, increased to about 15 minutes. With 4,000 visitors, the 2018 event also sold out.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/ein-maerchen-aus-eis-und-feuer-die-wacken-winter-nights-2018-gehen-zu-ende/|title=Ein M\u00e4rchen aus Eis und Feuer \u2013 Die Wacken Winter Nights 2018 gehen zu Ende!|last=|first=|date=25 February 2018|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> For the third event in 2019, the festival grounds were expanded considerably and 5,000 visitors attended. The fourth WWNs are planned for the 14th to 16 February 2020.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/die-wacken-winter-nights-2019-gehen-zu-ende/|title=Die Wacken Winter Nights 2019 gehen zu Ende!|last=|first=|date=24 February 2019|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Bands\n!Paying \nattendees\n!Price (EUR)\n!Sold out\n|-\n|2017\n|\n|3500\n|69,00\n|yes\n|-\n|2018\n|35\n|4000<ref name=\":8\" />\n|\n|yes\n|-\n|2019\n|34\n|5000<ref name=\":9\" />\n|89,99\n|\n|}\n\n=== StrongmanRun ===\nThe [[Fisherman's Friend StrongmanRun]] visited the Metal festival grounds of Wacken for the first time in April 2016. With their Wacken debut, the StrongmanRun season formally kicked off. About 3,000 participants, some in colourful costumes, took part in the run on the 20&nbsp;km track with 40 obstacles. In 2017, the StrongmanRun took place on the festival grounds.<ref>press kit ICS Network, ''Fisherman\u2019s Friend StrongmanRun Goes Heavy In Wacken'', September 2016 (p. 36)</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Rocks ===\nSeveral open-air festivals called Wacken Rocks were held in the past to transport the Wacken atmosphere to other places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bild.de/regional/hannover/festival-wacken-rocks-seaside-beginnt-in-9517326.bild.html|title=Festival \"Wacken rocks Seaside\" beginnt in Aurich|last=|first=|date=25 August 2009|website=BILD.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Full Metal Mountain ===\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde - Wacken Open Air 2016 51.jpg|thumb|Snowcat used as an advertising medium for Full Metal Mountain 2017]]\nDuring the winters of 2016, 2017 and 2018, an annual ski trip to [[Nassfeld]], Austria was organised for Metal fans under the name ''Full Metal Mountain''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.full-metal-mountain.com/de/news/news/news-detail/full-metal-mountain-das-datum-steht/|title=Full Metal Mountain \u2013 das Datum steht!|last=|first=|date=17 March 2015|website=full-metal-mountain.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Numerous bands and artists were present. For 2019, the festival was cancelled entirely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockmagazine.net/full-metal-mountain-2019-abgesagt/|title=Full Metal Mountain 2019 abgesagt\u2026|last=|first=|date=3 October 2018|website=Rockmagazine.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Full Metal Holiday ===\nPlanning and preparation are underway for a holiday trip to [[Mallorca]] with the title ''Full Metal Holiday - Destination Mallorca'', which will offer Metal concerts on the beach from 12 to 19 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.full-metal-holiday.com/de/|title=Full Metal Holiday|last=|first=|date=|website=full-metal-holiday.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The event was originally planned for 2017 and said to head to Ibiza, then rescheduled for 2018 and changed to Mallorca.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mallorcamagazin.com/nachrichten/gesellschaft/2017/10/12/58355/heavy-metal-reise-nach-mallorca-auf-2018-verschoben.html|title=Heavy-Metal-Reise nach Mallorca auf 2018 verschoben|last=|first=|date=12 October 2017|website=mallorcamagazin.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== W:O:A in numbers ==\nThe following chart shows the development of prices and visitor numbers of past festivals as published by the organisers. Prices refer to a 3-day ticket (incl. parking and camping) in pre-sale (without additional fees). \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Bands\n!Attendees\n!Paying\nattendees\n!Price\n!Sold out\n|-\n|1990\n|6\n|800\n|N/A\n|6,14\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|7\n|1.300\n|N/A\n|7,67\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|26\n|3.500\n|N/A\n|17,90\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|32\n|3.500\n|N/A\n|23,01\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|29\n|4.500\n|N/A\n|19,94\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|33\n|5.000\n|N/A\n|20,05\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|32\n|8.000\n|N/A\n|25,05\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|47\n|10.000\n|N/A\n|35,28\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|71\n|20.000\n|N/A\n|35,28\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|82\n|22.000\n|N/A\n|40,39\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|69\n|25.000\n|N/A\n|40,90\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|79\n|25.000\n|N/A\n|50,62\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|80\n|27.500\n|N/A\n|50,00\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|61\n|30.000\n|N/A\n|50,00\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|62\n|48.000\n|N/A\n|68,00\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|65\n|40.000\n|N/A\n|79,00\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|56\n|48.000\n|N/A\n|79,00\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|75\n|72.000\n|60.000\n|99,00\n|339 days\n|-\n|2008\n|71\n|75.000\n|N/A\n|109,00\n|221 days\n|-\n|2009\n|80\n|77.000\n|N/A\n|130,00\n|149 days\n|-\n|2010\n|123\n|82.500\n|75.000\n|130,00\n|247 days\n|-\n|2011\n|125\n|85.870<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2012/main-news/news/archiv/archiv-single/article/wacken-2011-ist-history-6858/|title=Wacken 2011 ist History.|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|130,00\n|187 days\n|-\n|2012\n|137\n|85.000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2013/main-news/news/ansicht/article/wacken-2012-ist-vorbei-7874/|title=Wacken 2012 ist History.|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|150,00\n|121 days\n|-\n|2013\n|135\n|84.500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-news/news/ansicht/article/wacken-2013-ist-history-8793/|title=Wacken 2013 ist History.|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|150,00\n|47 days\n|-\n|2014\n|132\n|84.500<ref name=\":6\" />\n|75.000\n|170,00\n|43 hours\n|-\n|2015\n|158\n|84.500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/das-woa-2015-ist-history/|title=Das W:O:A 2015 ist History!|last=|first=|date=2 August 2015|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|170,00\n|12 hours\n|-\n|2016\n|157\n|84.500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/das-woa-2016-ist-history/|title=Das W:O:A 2016 ist History!|last=|first=|date=7 August 2016|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|190,00\n|23 hours<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bild.de/regional/hamburg/wacken-open-air/wacken-2016-ausverkauft-42064084.bild.html|title=Wieder neuer Rekord! Wacken 2016 blitzartig ausverkauft|last=|first=|date=4 August 2015|website=bild.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|170\n|85.000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndr.de/unterhaltung/events/wacken_open_air/WOA-2017-Bands-Besucher-Geschichte,wacken4342.html|title=WOA 2017: Bands, Besucher, Geschichte|last=|first=|date=|website=ndr.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|75.000\n|220,00\n|309 days\n|-\n|2018\n|197\n|85.000\n|75.000\n|220,00\n|346 days\n|-\n|2019\n|\n|\n|75.000\n|221,00\n|4 days\n|-\n|2020\n|\n|\n|75.000\n|221,00\n|21 hours\n|}\n\n== Documentaries and reception \u00a0 ==\n[[File:Full metal village cast.jpg|thumb|From left to right: director [[Cho Sung-hyung|Cho Sung-Hyun]], presenter Bern St\u00f6lting and subjects of the film at the pre-premiere in Wacken: Uwe Trede, Klaus Pl\u00e4hn, Ann-Kathrin Schaak, Lore Trede, Irma Schaack]]\nSince 1999, various [[Documentary film|documentaries]] about W:O:A have been made. The first documentary, [[Metalheads - The Official Documentary]], was produced in 1999 on the occasion of the festival's 10th anniversary and was released on [[VHS]] by [[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] in 2000. The film team lived on the festival grounds for ten days prior to the actual start of the festival and documented the work of construction workers, farmers such as Uwe Trede, villagers, fans and organisers. Although the film shows excerpts from performances by some of the bands and interviews with the artists, it is more of a behind-the-scenes documentary. The film was produced with the simplest means, including a professional [[8 mm video format|Hi8]] and a [[DV|Mini-DV]] camera and a team of three, and was regarded by the organisers as a trial run on the subject of film. According to the organisers, a total of 10,000 copies were made and sold. The film ''Nordland'' was shot for the 15th edition of W:O:A, but was only used for internal promotion. Both films were made by Thomas Greiner.\n\nThe documentary [[Metal: A Headbanger's Journey|Metal - A Headbanger's Journey]] by [[Sam Dunn]] (2005) features Wacken Open Air. The festival is described as a [[Mecca]] of Heavy Metal. The film [[Full Metal Village]] by director [[Cho Sung-hyung|Cho Sung-Hyung]], made in 2005 and 2006, portrays the people of Wacken dealing with the festival. In 2006, she was awarded the main award of the [[Hessischer Filmpreis]] and the [[Schleswig-Holstein Filmpreis]] for best documentary. Full Metal Village was the first documentary ever to win the [[Max Oph\u00fcls]] Award for young filmmakers in 2007. [[WDR Fernsehen|WDR]]-[[Rockpalast]] profiled the festival in 2006,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/fernsehen/rockpalast/events/wacken-nullsechs-uebersicht-100.html|title=Wacken Open Air 2006|last=|first=|date=|website=wdr.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> 2007,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/fernsehen/rockpalast/events/wacken-sieben-uebersicht-100.html|title=Wacken Open Air 2007|last=|first=|date=|website=wdr.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> and 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/fernsehen/rockpalast/events/wacken-neun-uebersicht-100.html|title=Wacken Open Air 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=wdr.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> with two-hour documentaries. Broadcaster [[DMAX (TV channel)|DMAX]] also sent a camera team and produced a one-hour documentary on the construction of W:O:A in 2007.\n\n[[ZDF]] television filmed the 30-minute feature ''Ein Dorf und 100.000 Rockfans'' about Wacken Open Air 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628010322/http://doku.cc/2008/11/04/zdf-reportage-ein-dorf-und-100-000-rockfans-das-heavy-metal-festival-in-wacken/|title=ZDF reportage - Ein Dorf und 100.000 Rockfans - Das Heavy Metal Festival in Wacken|last=|first=|date=4 November 2008|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe aforementioned projects are almost identical in content; they invite visitors, organisers, and the citizens of Wacken to comment on the festival and generally present it in a positive way. However, there has been criticism of the fact that the Wacken Firefighters have been featured too prominently. The three Rockpalast documentaries focus on interviews with the musicians and the performances of the bands.\n\nAnother perspective is offered by the low-budget production ''Metaller die auf Br\u00fcste starren'' (\"The Metalheads Who Stare At Breasts\", title based on [[The Men Who Stare at Goats (film)|The Men Who Stare At Goats]]), which five festival attendees shot during their stay at Wacken. \"Offener Kanal Bad Offenbach\" is listed as its official producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.okbo.de/|title=OKBO \u2013 Homepage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The film shows the festival from the filmmakers\u2019 (subjective) point of view and comments on the events in the style of [[New Journalism]]. In contrast to other documentaries, this one focuses on the fans. Whether it's a documentary in the true sense of the word or whether the film is just entertainment remains controversial. The filmmakers themselves avoid this question and classify their work as a \"trash documentary\". The film premiered on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.programmkino.de/content/links.php?id=1516|title=Metaller die auf Br\u00fcste starren|last=|first=|date=|website=programmkino.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSchleswig-Holstein's Prime Minister [[Peter Harry Carstensen]] ([[CDU/CSU|CDU]]) commented on the opening of W:O:A 2009: \"I don't come here to listen to the music, but I do identify with the festival\".<ref>o. V., Wirtschaftswoche nr. 33/2009, p. 98</ref>\n\nSelected concerts of Wacken Open Air 2014 were broadcast live in an online stream. Furthermore, the cooperation between [[Spiegel Online]] and [[Arte]] made some performances available as [[video on demand]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/wacken-open-air-2014-live-livestream-des-heavy-metal-festivals-a-983491.html|title=Das Wacken Open Air live|last=|first=|date=30 July 2014|website=Spiegel ONLINE|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo mark its 30th anniversary, the [[Schleswig-Holsteinischer Zeitungsverlag|Norddeutsche Rundschau]] published a special edition that offered insights into the organisation of the Wacken Open Air. In addition, there will be a special exhibition at the Prinzesshof Kreismuseum in Itzehoe to mark the anniversary.\n\n=== Awards ===\n[[File:Wacken Heavy Metal Town 01.jpg|thumb|Fictional place-name sign at Wacken Open Air 2014]]\nAt an awards ceremony on 11 March 2008, W:O:A received the [[Live Entertainment Award]] (LEA) for best festival of 2007.\n\n=== Media ===\n\n==== Documentaries ====\nGerman television has produced numerous Wacken Open-Air documentaries in recent years. The following list is therefore not complete:\n\n* ''Metalheads'', documentary on the 10th anniversary of Wacken Open Air (director: Thomas Greiner)\n* ''Nordland'', documentary on the 15th anniversary of Wacken Open Air (director: Thomas Greiner (author))\n* [[Full Metal Village]], 2006 (Director: [[Cho Sung-hyung|Cho Sung-Hyung]])\n* ''Ein Dorf im Ausnahmezustand - A village in a state of emergency / Three days of Wacken - Bauernschlau und Heavy-Metal'', 2006 (film by Petra Petersen, [[NDR Fernsehen|NDR]])\n*[[File:Wacken Silo, 2013 DSC02930.JPG|thumb|The highly-visible silo of Raiffeisenhauptgenossenschaft in 2013]][[Rockpalast]] ([[Westdeutscher Rundfunk|WDR]]), Festival Wacken-Open-Air, 2006, 2007 and 2009, each approx. 2 h documentary, can be downloaded free of charge in the media library of the public broadcaster (as of February 2016)\n* ''Wahnsinn Wacken'', 2007 ([[DMAX (TV channel)|DMAX]]) approx. 1 h documentary<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dmax.de/programme/dmax-doku/videos/dmax-doku-wahnsinn-wacken/|title=Wahnsinn Wacken|last=|first=|date=|website=DMAX|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* ''Ein Dorf und 100.000 Rockfans'', 2008 (ZDF)\n* ''Metaller die auf Br\u00fcste starren'', 2010\n* ''Road To Wacken - The Movie'', 2011\n* ''Heavy Metal auf der Wiese'', 2011 (NDR) (Director: Manfred Studer)\n* ''Heavy Metal trifft Karniggels - Detlev Buck goes Wacken'', 2012 (NDR) (Director: Nils Utzig)\n* ''Heiter, harder, louder'', 2013 (NDR) (Director: Nils Utzig)\n* ''Alles auf Schwarz \u2013 Wacken!!! Sarnau und H\u00fcbner bei den Metalheads'', 2013 (NDR) (Director: Nils Utzig)\n* ''Wacken 3D'', 2014 (Director: Norbert Heitker) - also in 2D.\n* ''25 Years Louder Than Hell - The W:O:A Documentary'', Jun 2015, DVD and Blu-ray, 3 Eps. 45 min, 1 h 5 min, 42 min, original sound: German, English, and Spanish with subtitles in German, English.\n* ''Road To Wacken'', 2016 (DMAX) - two-part documentary (45 min each) about the band [[Blind Guardian]], who plan, prepare and perform their set at W:O:A, as well as the festival itself, its visitors, the village of Wacken and its inhabitants.<ref>http://www.dmax.de/programme/dmax-doku/videos/dmax-doku-road-to-wacken-teil-1/</ref><ref>http://www.dmax.de/programme/dmax-doku/videos/dmax-doku-road-to-wacken-teil-2/</ref>\n* ''Welcome to Wacken - A Documentary Film in Virtual Reality'', Jul 2017 (Director: Sam Dunn), \u00b0360 VR Film in English in five parts, with animations of the festival area.[87][88]\n* ''Der Wacken-Wahnsinn, Wie geht das?'' NDR Television, August 2018\n\n==== Official Wacken Open Air videos and DVDs ====\nThe organisers of Wacken Open Air have been releasing an official live DVD every year since 2003:\n\n* ''Metal Overdrive: Wacken Overdrive, 2003''\n* ''Armageddon Over Wacken 2003, 2003''\n* ''Armageddon Over Wacken 2004, 2004''\n* ''Armageddon Over Wacken 2005, 2005''\n* ''Wacken 2006 \u2013 Live at W:O:A, 2006''\n* ''Wacken 2007: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2007''\n* ''Wacken 2008: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2008''\n* ''Wacken 2009: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2009''\n* ''Wacken 2010: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2010''\n* ''Wacken 2011: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2011''\n* ''Wacken 2012: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2012''\n* ''Wacken 2013: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2014''\n* ''Wacken \u2013 Der Film, 2014''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/medien/arte-verfeuert-am-fussballabend-wacken-der-film-14319000.html|title=Arte zeigt \"Wacken - Der Film\": Darf es auch ein bisschen lauter sein?|last=|first=|date=2 July 2016|website=faz.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* ''25 Years of Wacken: Snapshots, Sraps, Thoughts & Sounds, 2015''\n* ''Wacken 2014: Live at Wacken Open Air, 2015''\n* ''Live At Wacken 2015 \u2013 26 Years Louder Than Hell, 2016''\n* ''Live at Wacken 2016 \u2013 27 Years Louder Than Hell, 2017''\n* ''Live at Wacken 2017 \u2013 28 Years Louder Than Hell, 2018''\n* ''Live at Wacken 2018 - 29 Years Louder Than Hell, 2019''\n* ''Live at Wacken 2019 - 30 Years Birthday Harder Louder than hell, 2019''\n\n==== Live albums by various bands ====\nNumerous bands have recorded their performances at Wacken Open Air and released them as audio CDs or DVDs. The following list contains only full live albums and no albums containing only individual live tracks from the festival:\n\n* [[Hypocrisy (band)|Hypocrisy]] \u2013 ''Hypocrisy destroys Wacken'', 1999\n* [[Rose Tattoo]] \u2013 ''25 to Live'', 2000\n* [[Tygers of Pan Tang]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken'', 2001\n* [[Grave Digger (band)|Grave Digger]] \u2013 ''Tunes Of Wacken'', 2002\n* [[Twisted Sister]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken: The Reunion'', 2005\n* [[Bloodbath]] \u2013 ''The Wacken Carnage'', 2005\n* [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken Open Air 2006''\n* [[Emperor (band)|Emperor]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken Open Air 2006''\n* [[Dimmu Borgir]] \u2013 ''The Invaluable Darkness'', 2007\n* [[Rage (German band)|Rage]] \u2013 ''Live in Wacken 2007'' (bonus DVD for the album [[Carved in Stone (Rage album)|Carved in Stone]]), 2008\n* [[Mambo Kurt]] \u2013 ''The Orgel Has Landed: Live at Wacken'', 2008\n* [[Avantasia]] \u2013 ''The Flying Opera'', 2008\n* [[Die Apokalyptischen Reiter]] \u2013 ''Tobsucht'' ''(Reitermania over Wacken & Party.San)'', 2008\n* [[Atheist (band)|Atheist]] \u2013 ''Unquestionable Presence: Live at Wacken'', 2009\n* [[Heaven & Hell (band)|Heaven & Hell]]: ''Neon Nights \u2013 Live at Wacken \u2013 30 Years of Heaven & Hell'' (CD & DVD format), 2009\n* [[Exodus (American band)|Exodus]] \u2013 ''Shovel Headed Tour Machine \u2013 Live at Wacken'', 2010\n* [[Grave Digger (band)|Grave Digger]] \u2013 ''The clans are still marching'', 2010\n* [[Immortal (band)|Immortal]] \u2013 ''The Seventh Date of Blashyrkh'', 2010\n* [[Rage (German band)|Rage]] \u2013 ''Live in Wacken 2009'' (bonus DVD for the album [[Strings to a Web]]), 2010\n* [[At the Gates]] \u2013 ''Purgatory Unleashed: Live at Wacken'', 2010\n* [[Running Wild (band)|Running Wild]] \u2013 ''The final Jolly Roger''\n* [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] \u2013 ''The W\u00f6rld Is Ours Vol. 2: Anyplace Crazy as Anywhere Else'', 2011\n* [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] \u2013 ''Heavy Metal Thunder \u2013 Live \u2013 Eagles Over Wacken'', 2012\n* [[Sacred Reich]] \u2013 ''Live At Wacken Open Air'', 2012\n* Degradead \u2013 ''Live at Wacken And Beyond'', 2012\n* [[Megaherz]] \u2013 ''G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung: Live At Wacken 2012'', 2012\n* [[Gorgoroth]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken 2008'', 2012\n* [[God Seed]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken'', 2012\n* [[Atrocity (band)|Atrocity]] \u2013 ''Die Gottlosen Jahre \u2013 Live In Wacken'', 2012\n* [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]] \u2013 ''Enjoy The Quiet: Live at Wacken 2012'', 2013\n* [[Airbourne (band)|Airbourne]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken 2011'', 2013\n* [[Nightwish]] \u2013 ''Showtime Storytime'', 2013\n* [[Alice Cooper]] \u2013 ''Raise The Dead : Live From Wacken'', 2014\n* [[Circle II Circle]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken (Official Bootleg)'', 2014\n* [[Deep Purple]] \u2013 ''From the Setting Sun \u2026 In Wacken'' (recorded in 2013), 2015\n* [[Sabaton (band)|Sabaton]] \u2013 ''Heroes On Tour'', 2015\n* [[Savatage]] \u2013 ''Return to Wacken'', 2015\n* [[Europe (band)|Europe]] \u2013 ''War Of Kings Special Edition, DVD/BluRay 2 Live at Wacken'', 2015\n* [[Danko Jones]] \u2013 ''Live at Wacken'' (recorded in 2015), 2016\n* [[Judas Priest]] \u2013 ''Battle Cry'', 2016\n* [[Unisonic (band)|Unisonic]] \u2013 ''Live in Wacken'', 2017\n* [[Hansen & Friends]] \u2013 ''Thank You Wacken live'', 2017\n* [[Arch Enemy]] \u2013 ''As The Stages Burn!'' (recorded in 2016), 2017\n* [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] \u2013 ''Down Down & Dirty at Wacken'' (recorded in 2017), 2018\n* [[Accept (band)|Accept]] \u2013 ''Symphonic Terror - Live at Wacken 2017'', 2018\n\n==== Further reception ====\nIn her crime novels [[Tod in Wacken]] and [[Der Teufel von Wacken]], author [[Heike Denzau]] places her storylines at Wacken Open Air, describing the location as well as the festival and its visitors.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tod in Wacken|last=Denzau|first=Heike|publisher=Emons Verlag|year=2013|isbn=978-3-95451-064-1|location=Cologne|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Till Burgw\u00e4chter: ''Zwischen Aasb\u00fcttel und Vahlenmoor. Die Wahrheit!!! \u2013 \u00fcber Wacken''. Oidium, Berlin 2004, {{ISBN|3-9809697-5-4}} \u2192 edition 2011; {{ISBN|978-3-934896-35-2}}.\n*Andreas Sch\u00f6we: ''Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt. 2.'', updated and extended edition. Hannibal Verlag, H\u00f6fen 2012, {{ISBN|978-3-85445-376-5}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Wacken Open Air}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.wacken.com}}\n*[http://www.wackenradio.com/ Official Wacken Radio]\n* [https://www.ics-int.com/ Website of ICS (organiser)]\n* [https://www.wacken.com/en/all-information/history/ Festival history with a list of the bands that have performed]\n\n{{Coord|54|01|42|N|9|21|22|E|display=title|region:DE-NI_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n[[Category:Heavy metal festivals in Germany]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1990]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German heavy metal music festival}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox music festival |\n  | music_festival_name = Wacken Open Air\n  | image = Festivalgel\u00e4nde - 2017215225222 2017-08-03 Wacken - Sven - 1D X MK II - 1539 - B70I9471.jpg\n  | caption = The burning skull is the official symbol for Wacken Open Air\n  | location = [[Wacken, Schleswig-Holstein|Wacken]], Germany\n  | years_active = 1990\u2013present\n  | genre = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]}}\n  | website = [https://www.wacken.com/en/ www.wacken.com]\n}}\n{{Listen\n|filename=We are the metalheads.ogg\n|title=We Are the Metalheads (2009)\n|description=The official Wacken Hymn, performed by [[Doro (musician)|Doro]] and Skyline.\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n'''Wacken Open Air''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|n}}, stylised '''W:O:A''') is a [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] [[music festival]], held annually since 1990 on the first weekend of August in the town of [[Wacken, Schleswig-Holstein|Wacken]] in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. Almost all styles of [[hard rock]] and metal are represented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://disctopia.de/live-and-ontour/metal-festivals-in-deutschland-osterreich-schweiz/|title=Metal Festival Landkarte 2015 f\u00fcr Deutschland & \u00d6sterreich {{!}} Disctopia Metal Webzine|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> It is now one of the largest heavy metal festivals in the world and one of the largest open-air festivals in Germany. Between 2011-2018, the number of attendees was around 85,000, 75,000 of whom were paying visitors. In 2020, the festival is scheduled to take place from 30 July to 1 August.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nThe idea for Wacken Open Air was conceived in 1989 when Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner visited a restaurant together. Both lived in Wacken and were friends, Jensen played the electric bass with [[Rock music|Rock]] cover band Skyline. From its beginnings until 1992, the band was composed of Ines Jeske from [[Vaale]] (vocals), Thomas Jensen from Wacken (bass), Peter Huhn from Wacken (electric guitar), Dennis Harman from [[Itzehoe]] (keyboard), and Andreas G\u00f6ser from Wacken (drums). Skyline was one of the first regional Metal and Rock [[cover band]]s at that time. The band was regionally known, working its way from appearances in village pubs and gigs at biker meetings up to an appearance as supporting band of \"[[Extrabreit]]\". H\u00fcbner was a disc jockey with a focus on Rock music and Heavy Metal. Jensen and H\u00fcbner developed the idea to organise an [[open-air concert]] in a gravel pit in Wacken and persuaded Skyline drummer Andreas G\u00f6ser and J\u00f6rg Jensen, Thomas Jensen's brother, to help make it happen. Until then, the pit had already served as a meeting venue for up to 3,000 members of biker club 'No Mercys', it was therefore perfectly suited for their plans and also presented an opportunity to attract motorcycle fans. From the beginning, it was clear that the focus of the event would be on Rock and Metal and that, in contrast to other single-day festivals such as [[Monsters of Rock]] or Super Rock in [[Mannheim]], there would also be camping grounds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=18\u201319}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|date=Spring 2013|title=Das W:O:A \u2013 Die Story in Zeitraffer|url=|journal=Wacken inside|volume=|pages=16\u201319|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Early years and initial development ===\n[[File:Wacken Promotion 1990.jpg|thumb|Advertisement for Wacken Open Air in 1990]]\nThe first two-day festival took place in the gravel pit on 24 and 25 August 1990 and barely had 800 visitors. The performing bands all hailed from Germany, and apart from Skyline, bands like 5th Avenue, Motoslug, Sacred Season, Axe 'n Sex, and Wizzard played. The first festivals were organised privately, with the technology being built on a trailer borrowed from a local trucking company and the stage being a DIY construction.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt.|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=19\u201322}}</ref>\n\nIn subsequent years, too, most of the tasks were carried out by the small team. Until August 1994, for example, ticket orders were organised privately by Andy G\u00f6ser's mother Regina G\u00f6ser and security duties were performed by friendly motorcycle clubs up until 1996.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=22\u201324}}</ref> In 1991, the number of visitors increased to 1.300,<ref name=\":2\" /> and with Skyline returning, Bon Scott, an [[AC/DC]] cover band from [[Hamburg]], Gypsy Kyss, Kilgore, Life Artist, Ruby Red, and Shanghai'd Guts joined them on stage for an all-regional roster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-history/history/woa-1991/bands/|title=Billing 1991|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> That same year, the iconic skull logo was designed by Mark Ramsauer after the basic shape had been determined by Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/schleswig-holstein/woa-2019-wikipedia-fakt-oder-fiktion-wacken-gruender-machen-faktencheck-id24948137.html|title=WOA 2019: Wikipedia Fakt oder Fiktion: Wacken-Gr\u00fcnder machen Faktencheck|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The cow skull refers to the venue, a meadow for cows, and to Jensen and H\u00fcbner as \"boys from the village\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockhard.de/megazine/heftarchiv/online-megazine/kolumne/25-jahre-wacken.html|title=25 Jahre Wacken|last=Eckhorst|first=Tim|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the programme changed to include internationally renowned bands such as [[Blind Guardian]] and [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]] for the first time,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=24\u201326}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> and the number of bands rose to 26, listing bands from [[Sweden]], the [[United States|USA]], [[Ireland]], and [[Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-history/history/woa-1992/1/|title=Billing 1992|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The organisers used a professional stage with lighting and PA for the first time and were able to win cigarette brand Prince Denmark as a sponsor.<ref name=\":3\" /> That year, the Party Stage was set up in the DJ tent next to the main stage, where cover bands and fun projects were to perform exclusively. The additional post-concert costs for garbage disposal on the campground, where 2,500 paying guests and many more were present and celebrated, as well as the significantly oversized security, among other things, meant that the organisers recorded a loss of around 25,000 D-Mark that year.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWith the reunion of the band [[Fates Warning]] at the festival in 1993, Wacken Open Air had a special feature and also made a name for itself in the following years with unusual band constellations and reunions. At the same time, [[Doro (musician)|Doro Pesch]] and other well-known bands made for interesting appearances, which resulted in a new record attendance of 3,500 paying customers. Simultaneously, the team tried their hand at concert organisation and, under the moniker Stone Castle Promotion, held a [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] concert for 2,000 people in Flensburg which, unfortunately, could not cover its promotional costs. A show with [[Dio (band)|Dio]]/Freak of Nature became a disaster with only 167 tickets sold, and together with the Open Air, which again recorded a minus, the organisers incurred debts of around 350,000 D-Mark. As a result, J\u00f6rg Jensen and Andreas G\u00f6ser left the team; Holger H\u00fcbner and Thomas Jensen remained, as did J\u00f6rn-Ulf Goesmann for another two years, continuing to run the Wacken Open Air despite the debts for which their parents had provided guarantees. During the same year, Thomas Jensen's mother died and Holger H\u00fcbner had a serious accident \u2013 the year went down in Wacken history as the \"year of the plague\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=27\u201330}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn its fifth anniversary in 1994, the financial situation stabilised and the festival finally broke even. The line-up remained professional and featured many internationally known bands from the [[Metal scene]]. A total of 4,500 tickets were sold; on top of that, due to the rising costs of garbage disposal, tickets for the camping grounds had to be purchased separately, and pre-orders were rewarded with a free T-shirt.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=30\u201331}}</ref> Also in 1995, income and expenses evened out thanks to the commitment of bands such as [[Tiamat (band)|Tiamat]], [[D.A.D. (band)|D-A-D]], the [[Pretty Maids]], and [[Angra (band)|Angra]]. But even with roughly 5,000 attendees, the festival didn\u2019t turn a profit.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt|last=Sch\u00f6we|first=Andreas|publisher=H\u00f6fen|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=32\u201333}}</ref> However, for the first time, national media became aware of Wacken Open Air, especially [[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] magazine, as well as the newly founded TV station [[VIVA Germany|VIVA]] with its Heavy Metal programme ''Metalla''.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== First achievements and growth ===\nTicket sales for the 1996 festival again started sluggishly, despite a headliner like [[Kreator]] and numerous internationally renowned bands such as [[The Exploited]], [[Gorefest]], and [[Crematory (band)|Crematory]]. Management tried to prevent another loss by securing more acts and finally managed to get [[B\u00f6hse Onkelz]] to perform. The engagement of the controversial band also led to criticism, and some bands cancelled their gig in Wacken that year. Cologne band [[Brings]] called off their gig on short notice and offered to refund their fans\u2019 ticket prices.<ref>\u201eNews\" from Hamburger Abendblatt, 6. August 1996, p. 12</ref>\n\nAs a result of many visitors flooding the village in 1996, the inhabitants of Wacken voiced their concern over an event of this size being held in the local gravel pit. Uwe Trede offered to relocate the festival site to his own property and the areas previously used as campgrounds and took care of the acquisition of additional land. The organisational team grew to include Thomas Hess as production manager, who had previously been active as tour manager for Die B\u00f6hsen Onkelz, as well as Sheree Hesse for catering to the artists and VIPs. With the W.E.T.-Stage, a third stage was set up in 1997. The \"Wacken Evolution Tent\" was to be made available primarily to newcomers and bands without record deals. That year, the number of visitors reached 10,000 for the first time, with [[Rockbitch]]'s erotic stage show causing a scene.<ref>Andreas Sch\u00f6we: ''Wacken Roll \u2013 Das gr\u00f6\u00dfte Heavy Metal-Festival der Welt''. H\u00f6fen 2012, p. 35\u201337</ref>\n\n=== Further development of the festival ===\n[[File:WackenOpenAir.jpg|thumb|W:O:A 2005 was attended by 40,000 people]]\nOver the years, the size of Wacken Open Air has grown continuously, and now dozens of bands and tens of thousands of visitors flock to the festival. Even though the organisers said in 2006 that 62,500 visitors were \"the limit of what is possible\",<ref>press conference in 2006 (source needed)</ref> changes were made to the structure of the festival grounds the following year by allocating a larger area to the \"Party Stage\". In addition, tickets could no longer be purchased directly on the festival grounds to reduce the number of spontaneous or ticketless visitors. In 2007 and 2008, the festival had already sold out as a result of advance ticket sales; for W:O:A 2009, tickets had even sold out by the end of 2008. The tickets for 2010, too, sold out months in advance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2010/main-news/news/ansicht/article/wahnsinn-wacken-im-5-jahr-hintereinander-ausverkauft-resttickets-bei-unseren-buspartnern-erhaeltli/|title=News on wacken.com|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhile the festival originally only lasted two days, the performances have been lasting from Thursday to Saturday, i.e. three days, for some years. Thursday became a \"Night to Remember\", with mainly \"classical\" Heavy Metal bands appearing, such as the [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]] in 2006. On the actual Party Stage, younger and more modern bands play as a contrast to the \"Night to Remember\". In addition, the event is accompanied by a rich complementary programme; in addition to a merchant area \u2013 obligatory for music festivals \u2013 a beer garden has been operating since 2000, in which the [[Wacken Firefighters]]' marching band opens the festival before its official start. On Thursday in 2007, the \"Hellfest Stage\" was initiated. Since 2009, there has been a \"Medieval Stage\", where mainly [[Middle Ages|Medieval]] and [[Folk metal|Folk Metal]] bands play.\n\nThe fact that many well-known bands, including the Scorpions, [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]], [[Twisted Sister]], [[Dimmu Borgir]], [[Slayer]], and [[Helloween]], have recorded live [[DVD]]s at Wacken, shows how esteemed the Open Air has since become. Ahead of their farewell tour in 2004, Die B\u00f6hsen Onkelz also performed an extended set at W:O:A.\n\nSince 2002, the so-called \"Metal Train\" has been travelling from [[Z\u00fcrich|Zurich]] to Wacken and back before and after the festival to bring fans to the Northern German village and provide a matching entertainment programme. Bus tours from [[Scandinavia]]n countries, especially [[Sweden]], but also from [[Austria]], are organised each year and used by several hundred fans.\n\nThe \"W:O:A Soccercup\" has been taking place annually since 2002. This football tournament, which started with nine teams and takes place on Wednesdays, has grown over the years and has been held in World Cup mode with 32 teams since 2007 (a one-off event in 2011 featured 36 teams). The international teams register in advance and are composed of festival visitors. For the tournament's 15th anniversary in 2016, a band was featured and took part for the first time: [[Serum 114]] formed a team with several fans and were able to win the tournament. Although it is meant to be a fun tournament, in which creative outfits and names take precedence over athletic performance, the award ceremony after the tournament has been held on one of the stages since 2013 and prices can be won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808210920/http://neu.woa-soccercup.de/|title=W:O:A Soccercup|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the \"Full Metal Church\" took place in Wacken for the first time. Marking the local church's 150th anniversary, the team, together with the parish, organised a concert by the band [[Faun (band)|Faun]], which was framed by two readings and sermons by \"[[Volxbibel]]\" author Martin Dreyer. Both the concert and the services were completely overcrowded by festival visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_kAR2EWlgk|title=Full Metal Church|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Present ===\n[[File:Alice Cooper - Wacken Open Air 2017 03.jpg|left|thumb|Alice Cooper at Wacken Open Air 2017]]\nThe festival is one of the Metal scene's highlights of the year. Nowadays, about a third of the visitors, some of whom arrive quite some time before the official start of the festival, and the majority of the bands come from abroad. According to the organisers, 2018 saw visitors from more than 80 nations attending the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/die-ersten-bands-fuer-das-wacken-open-air-2019/|title=Die ersten Bands f\u00fcr das Wacken Open Air 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe number of participants increased to 75,000 in 2008 and included 65,000 paying guests. In 2008, the festival sold out twice ( W:O:A 2008 in spring and W:O:A 2009 on 31 December 2008).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2010/main-news/news/archiv/archiv-single/article/wahnsinn-wacken-sold-out/|title=Wahnsinn Wacken \u2013 Sold Out!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs is common with festivals of this size, Wacken Open Air received criticism for its hygienic conditions, prices, security personnel, as well as for the overcrowding and commercial orientation of the event. These points of criticism were addressed by making further substantial investments in the festival's fixed and mobile infrastructure. In 2008, the organisers also contributed 1,000,000 Euros to the expansion of Wacken\u2019s local outdoor swimming pool in order to make the festival even more attractive to the residents and visitors of the town.<ref>Information provided by mayor Axel Kunkel</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the festival has been running an [[Internet radio|online radio]] station called [[Wacken Radio]], which broadcasts Metal music around the clock. It is being produced in cooperation with [[RauteMusik.FM|RauteMusik]] as of February 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rautemusik.fm/wackenradio/|title=Wacken Metal Radio \u2013 Heavy Metal Radio \u2013 Metalcore & Grindcore \u2013 RauteMusik.FM Internetradio|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Wikipedians at WOA 2011.JPG|thumb|Attendees at Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nFor the 23rd edition of Wacken Open Air, the sale of an \"X-Mas Package\" started on Monday, 8 August 2011, shortly after the end of that year's festival, and was sold out within 45 minutes. The event sold out ten times in a row between 2006 and 2015. Tickets for Wacken Open Air 2015 sold out after just 12 hours on 4 August 2014 \u2013 just a few hours after the end of W:O:A 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2014/main-tickets-shop/tickets/-/|title=Das W:O:A ist zum zehnten Mal SOLD OUT!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The X-Mas Tickets for W:O:A 2016, which cost 10 Euros less and whose buyers were entitled to a free T-shirt, were completely sold out only 20 minutes after the start of pre-sales. Booking office Metaltix\u2019 servers were highly busy. In the minutes before the start of the pre-sale, the pages were no longer accessible; after that, [[Network traffic|data traffic]] had to be limited by wait lists.\n\nPrices for the festival have risen and are currently at a level similar to other major Rock festivals, such as [[Rock am Ring and Rock im Park|Rock am Ring]] and [[Hurricane Festival]]. After several years of success in which the festival sold out within hours, the first 60,000 tickets for the 2017 festival were sold in mid-2016. 55,000 tickets were sold within the first hour. By the end of April 2017, the festival was almost sold out except for a few remaining tickets. The price for the festival ticket was 220 Euros, but there was no fee for early arrival campers, who often set up their elaborately designed accommodations before the festival begins \u2013 partly to get the best spots near the festival grounds. In addition, all toilets and showers were free in 2017.\n\nThe festival sold out within a few days each in 2014-2016. However, the last tickets for the 2017 festival were sold after 309 days, a mere 2 months before the start of the festival, even though only 10,000 tickets remained after the first day of sales. This was a matter of speculation at first, and reasons such as the changed security situation or the price development were taken into account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/themen/wacken-open-air/holger-huebner-darum-ist-das-woa-2017-noch-nicht-ausverkauft-id14616776.html|title=Holger H\u00fcbner: Darum ist das WOA 2017 noch nicht ausverkauft|last=|first=|date=20 August 2016|website=SHZ.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Regardless of that, the festival sold out for the 13th time in a row in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/themen/wacken-open-air/woa-ist-ausverkauft-alle-75-000-tickets-sind-weg-id17048861.html|title=WOA ist ausverkauft \u2013 alle 75.000 Tickets sind weg|last=|first=|date=13 June 2017|website=SHZ.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2018 Thomas Hess, the festival's longtime production (and former security) director, passed away. He had joined festival management in 1996 as a former tour manager of B\u00f6hse Onkelz and was considered one of the most important leading figures for the festival, along with the remaining founders and the Trede family, who organise the camping areas and the camping supervisors as subcontractors. He made a significant contribution to the W:O:A being so well organised, peaceful and successful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/nachruf-thomas-hess/|title=Nachruf Thomas Hess|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nWacken Open Air 2018 was named the best major festival at the European Festival Awards 2018 and best festival at the Helga! Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/best-major-festival-das-woa-2018-gewinnt-bei-den-european-festival-awards/|title=Best Major Festival \u2013 das W:O:A 2018 gewinnt bei den European Festival Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> For W:O:A 2019, all 75,000 tickets were sold within the first four days of sales, making this the 14th time in a row that the festival completely sold out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/das-30-wacken-open-air-ist-ausverkauft/|title=Das 30. Wacken Open Air ist ausverkauft!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:Wacken 2011 Impression 05.JPG|thumb|Sanitary facilities on the camping grounds with illuminated \"sign of the horns\", Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nThe organisers of Wacken Open Air founded ''Stone Castle Rockpromotions'' in 1990 in order to organise the first festival. The name is derived from the direct translation of \"Steinburg\" from the district of [[Steinburg]], to which Wacken belongs.<ref name=\":1\" /> Stone Castle remained the company\u2019s name until 1996. Up until 2014, the headquarters were located in [[D\u00f6rpstedt|D\u00f6rpstedt (Schleswig-Flensburg district)]] and then moved to Wacken. The company's name has been ''ICS'' (International Concert Service) GmbH since 1999. The company owns the label ''Wacken Records'' and the [[Mail order|mailorder]] Metaltix, among others.\n\nA daily festival newspaper has been available since 2007, reporting on what's happening on the festival grounds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Metall macht Musik|last=Eckhorst|first=Tim|publisher=TheNextArt Verlag|year=2008|isbn=978-3-939400-18-9|location=|pages=83}}</ref> The Thursday edition is also included free of charge with all newspapers published by [[Schleswig-Holsteinischer Zeitungsverlag]].\n\nIn 2014, the online radio station RauteMusik took over production of the official Wacken radio. Wacken Radio has its own container on the festival grounds every year, where it reports live.\n\nUp until a few years ago, Wacken\u2019s official town signs were either replaced by plastic signs spelling Heavy Metal Town during W:O:A or bolted more tightly because they were often stolen as souvenirs. Some shops are now selling black cotton bags with the Wacken town sign on one side and the words \"This town sign I may keep\" on the other.\n\nAn action for exceeding the maximum noise limit, brought before the Administrative Court of Schleswig by residents of Wacken, ended in January 2013 with an out-of-court settlement. Now, if the average noise level of the festival exceeds 70&nbsp;dB, the organisers pay 1,000 Euros to the community, which donates the money to charitable causes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/musik-festival-wacken-darf-laut-bleiben-a-879534.html|title=Anwohner bes\u00e4nftigt: Wacken darf weiter rocken|last=|first=|date=|website=Spiegel Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nThe site covers more than 240 [[hectare]]s, which are divided by more than 45 kilometres of fence. The inner area, including the main stage, has a size of 43,000 [[square metre]]s. More than 1,300 toilets and almost 500 showers are available for the 75,000 paying attendees. 2,200 trucks with equipment are needed for the entire festival. Stage construction and dismantling usually take 7 days and 5 days respectively. For this, 75 trucks of stage equipment (1,000 tons), 10 trucks of sound equipment and 27 trucks of lighting equipment are used.<ref name=\":5\">W:O:A press kit 2018</ref>\n\nSince 2014, the [[Electricity|electric]] output has amounted to 12 megawatts, roughly matching the needs of a small town counting 70,000 inhabitants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wacken.shz.de/woa2014/|title=Wacken - 25 Jahre Metal-Mythos|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.saz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> In addition, 40 diesel-fuelled [[Emergency power system|emergency power generators]] are required. 25 electricians are responsible for the power supply.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n600,000 Euros were spent on the construction of sewage systems and the improvement of power supply on the festival grounds. At the same time, 700,000 Euros worth of drains were installed in front of the stages in order to improve the drainage of water masses during heavy rains. The main paths were also paved with 10&nbsp;km of mobile roads to facilitate access for rescue vehicles.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nA total of approximately 5,000 employees work for the festival, including 1,800 security staff members, 150 cleaners, 70 construction and dismantling assistants, as well as 400 police officers, 250 firefighters, 900 paramedics, and six emergency doctors.\n\nIn 2017, a beer pipeline measuring one kilometer to supply ten dispensing systems was used for the first time. At full capacity, this construction allowed for 10,000 litres of beer to be tapped within the hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/kultur/musik/wacken-open-air-2017-bier-pipeline-liefert-10000-liter-pro-stunde_aid-17915041|title=Wacken Open Air 2017: Bier-Pipeline liefert 10.000 Liter pro Stunde|last=|first=|date=|website=RP Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stages ===\n[[File:Nightwish - Wacken Open Air 2018-1769.jpg|thumb|Faster/Harder Stages at Wacken Open Air 2018]]\nWacken Open Air now boasts eight stages for musicians and accompanying entertainment. The most important ones are the Faster and the Harder Stage, which are designed as connected twin stages and have a shared sound and lighting system. Together with the slightly smaller Louder Stage, these two stages make up the Infield, or The Holy Ground. All three stages are also equipped with [[video wall]]s to allow visibility of the performers even from remote positions.\n\nUp until 2016, these three stages were called Black Stage, True Metal Stage, and Party Stage. After Wacken 2016, visitors were encouraged to suggest new names. From these suggestions, the best ideas were to be put up to a vote in a survey. Instead, however,\u00a0 the slogan \"Faster - Harder - Louder\" became the inspiration for the names and the three stages were renamed accordingly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/mehr-sound-und-neue-namen-die-buehnen-im-infield/|title=Mehr Sound und neue Namen \u2013 die B\u00fchnen im Infield!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo more twin stages, the W.E.T. Stage (Wacken Evolution Tent) and the Headbanger Stage, are located inside a big tent called Bullhead City Circus. The Metal Battle takes place on these stages on Wednesday and Thursday, followed by regular band appearances on the days after.\n\nWhile the large stages and tent stages are open to all genres, the remaining stages are dedicated to specific themes. The Wackinger Stage is located in the medieval area of the festival and is played primarily by bands from Folk, Pagan and Medieval genres, while the Wasteland Stage, which was established in 2014, is geared towards music with an apocalyptic touch. The Beergarden Stage is modelled after typical folk festival stages, but also accommodates permanent Wacken guests such as the Wacken Firefighters and [[Mambo Kurt]].\n\n=== Event area ===\n[[File:Wastelander \u2013 Wacken Open Air 2014 05.jpg|thumb|Wasteland \u2013 apocalypse at Wacken Open Air 2014]]\nWacken Open Air's event area is divided into several structurally separated sections. Since 2014, only one major security check is performed upon entering the grounds, after that, only the festival wristbands are checked.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/ein-vierteljahrhundert-wacken-open-air-ist-history/|title=Ein Vierteljahrhundert Wacken Open Air ist History!!!|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpecial features of the W:O:A include the Wackinger area, which resembles a medieval market and contains specialty food and beverage stalls as well as the Wackinger Stage, where matching music is played. Various walking acts also entertain the audience. This area borders on the Wasteland designed by the [[Wasteland Warriors]], where a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] world and stage (Wastelandstage) styled in homage to the [[Mad Max (franchise)|Mad Max]]-franchise is set up.\n\nThe area in front of the main stages comprises both the [[Bavaria]]n [[beer garden]] and a large shopping mile called Metal Markt. There are also various food stalls, the Wacken Foundation Camp, ATMs, and the Movie Field, where Heavy Metal [[Documentary film|documentaries]] and [[feature film]]s are screened.\n\nThe most important stages, the focal point of the festival, are located in the so-called Infield, which can be reached only via the Center. In addition to these stages, it also hosts food and beverage stalls.\n\n=== Camping grounds ===\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde Wasteland - Wacken Open Air 2016-AL0321.jpg|thumb|Wasteland festival grounds at Wacken Open Air 2016]]\nAs Wacken Open Air only sells 3-day tickets, the majority of visitors spend the entire festival on-site. As a result, most of the more than 240 hectares of the festival site are designated camping areas. Camping opens on Monday and has been included in the ticket price since 2017. However, in the years before, an extra fee was charged for arrival before Wednesday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/news-details/infos-zum-vorverkauf-fuer-das-woa-2017/|title=Infos zum Vorverkauf f\u00fcr das W:O:A 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe campsite is equipped with showers, flushing toilets, [[portable toilet]]s, [[drinking fountain]]s, small supermarkets, food stalls, and information boards, and is continuously patrolled by the police, fire brigade, and security services. A garbage collection service collects full garbage bags on the premises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2015/main-news/news/news-suche/suche-ansicht/article/metal4nature-2014-9413/|title=Metal4nature|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor orientation, the individual sites called Campgrounds are marked with code letters. Campgrounds A and B are reserved for visitors arriving without a car, while Campgrounds Y and R are intended for campers and other heavy-duty vehicles. Y offers the possibility to rent entire caravans, tents or to get a power supply for your own [[Caravan (towed trailer)|caravan]]. At Campground U, large groups of 50 people or more can reserve a larger area free of charge.\n\nSince the large crowds lead to a bottleneck situation in terms of mobile service, some providers now set up portable [[base station]]s for [[GSM]], [[UMTS]], and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]+ during the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vodafone.de/featured/?vf_origin_url=music/wacken-nature-one-und-co-vodafone-ruestet-sein-netz-fuer-den-festivalsommer/|title=Wacken, Nature One und Co. \u2013 Vodafone r\u00fcstet sein Netz f\u00fcr den Festivalsommer|last=|first=|date=|website=vodafone.de|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical services ===\nA festival of this size needs capable medical services, which here are called the Wacken Rescue Squad. Every year, hundreds of helpers from various relief organisations from all over Germany arrive before the festival to prepare the medical camp and care for people in need during the event. The medical service is managed by the local [[German Red Cross|DRK]] association in [[Kaltenkirchen]].\n\nThe visiting and local relief organisations provide vehicles and material during the course of the festival. These include ambulances and radios for communication in particular. Due to the road conditions, quads and foot patrols are often used in Wacken, especially in the vicinity of the medical centre. In addition to the medical service, which counts approx. 270 people at peak times, the rescue service cooperation Schleswig-Holstein has more than ten emergency vehicles (ambulances and mobile intensive care units) on site while coordinating the overall [[emergency management]].\n\nIn 2013, around 3,300 people received medical care from approximately 500 paramedics.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20130804124442/http://www.ndr.de/unterhaltung/events/wacken/woa_2013/wacken2849.html|title=Wacken-Fans machen sich auf den Heimweg|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Crime and accidents ===\nDespite the size of the festival, no serious security problems have been encountered so far. Disputes among visitors are rare, and in 2011, a total of 20 reports of bodily injury was filed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studium.at/139030-wacken-2011-95000-fans-rockten-weltweit-groessten-heavy-metal-festival|title=Wacken 2011: 95.000 Fans rockten am weltweit gr\u00f6\u00dften Heavy Metal Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=studium.at|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The main problem consists of several hundred reported thefts each year. In 2011, police were able to arrest three gangs of thieves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/panorama/gesellschaft/heavy-metal-treffen-polizei-schnappt-drei-diebesbanden-in-wacken-a-778666.html|title=Heavy-Metal-Treffen: Polizei schnappt drei Diebesbanden in Wacken|last=|first=|date=|website=Spiegel Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> In comparison to other events of this scale, the festival is classified by police as secure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fr-online.de/panorama/wacken-open-air-2012-unfalltod-ueberschattet-wacken-bilanz,1472782,16811984.html|title=Unfalltod \u00fcberschattet Wacken-Bilanz|last=|first=|date=|website=Franfurter Rundschau online|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSo far there have been four deaths and some serious injuries:\n\n* In 2005, a heavily intoxicated 37-year-old crashed into an ambulance moving at walking pace and succumbed to his head injuries in the hospital. To support his family, organisers held a fundraising event; W:O:A 2006 honoured the deceased with a minute's silence.\n* In 2011, a rioting fan was overwhelmed by security guards in the village and died of [[Cardiac arrest|cardiovascular arrest]].\n* In 2012, a 22-year-old festival visitor went to sleep near a [[Electric generator|generator]] and breathed in its [[carbon monoxide]] fumes. He could not be revived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/panorama/welt/todesfall-bei-musik-festival-in-wacken-metal-fan-leblos-aufgefunden_aid_793853.html|title=Todesfall bei Musik-Festival in Wacken: Metal-Fan leblos aufgefunden|last=|first=|date=|website=Focus online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* In 2013, a 52-year-old visitor from Poland died of natural causes in his tent. That same year, a fan was seriously injured when the cartridge of his camping stove exploded for unknown reasons.<ref name=\":7\" />\n* In 2016, two men were injured when one of them set fire to illegal [[firecracker]]s and the other tried to stop him. Reports that one of the men's ears had been torn off turned out to be false.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/regionales/schleswig-holstein/boeller-explosion-in-wacken-feuerwehrmann-es-war-alles-ganz-anders-id14544331.html|title=B\u00f6ller-Explosion in Wacken \u2013 Feuerwehrmann: \"Es war alles ganz anders\"|last=|first=|date=|website=shz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n* In 2017, a 16-year-old was seriously injured while trying to refill a [[Portable stove|camping stove]] with [[denatured alcohol]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kn-online.de/Nachrichten/Schleswig-Holstein/Verbrennungen-16-Jaehriger-beim-WOA-verletzt|title=16-J\u00e4hriger beim Wacken Open Air verletzt|last=|first=|date=1 August 2017|website=Kieler Nachrichten|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Commitment ==\n\n=== Metal Battle ===\n[[File:Metal Battle - 2017216154323 2017-08-04 Wacken - Sven - 5DS R - 0106 - 5DSR2534.jpg|thumb|The 2017 winners of Metal Battle, Mexican band Jet Jaguar]]\nW:O:A Metal Battle is an international band contest first held in 2004. During Metal Battle, newcomer bands compete against each other in national qualifiers and finals; the winner of each country then competes against the other finalists in the grand final at Wacken Open Air.\n\nAn international jury selects the competition's best bands. In earlier years, winners of the competition were offered a record deal, whereas nowadays, the five best bands receive cash or material prices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-battle.com/about/|title=Metal Battle|last=|first=|date=|website=Metal Battle|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Foundation ===\nThe [[Wacken Foundation]] was founded in 2009 by the festival\u2019s organisers and serves as a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|charitable foundation]]. Its objective is to support young bands from the Heavy Metal genre.\n\nSponsorship is granted to specific projects such as the production of a [[Compact disc|CD]] or the realisation of a tour. In addition, the Wacken Foundation provides information about its projects at many [[Europe]]an festivals each summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wacken-foundation.com/home/|title=Wacken Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=Wacken Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Since the 2017/2018 season, the Wacken Foundation's lettering can be found on the jerseys of German 3rd league club [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]. This was facilitated by jersey sponsors [[Heaven Shall Burn]], whose [[logo]] has been moved to the jersey's sleeve for this cause. Part of the proceeds from the jersey\u2019s sale is donated to the foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/ost-thueringen/carl-zeiss-jena-wacken-sponsor-trikotsponsor-100.html|title=Carl Zeiss Jena l\u00e4uft mit Wacken auf der Brust auf|last=|first=|date=|website=mdr.de|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Music Camp ===\n2014 saw Wacken Music Camp take place for the first time. One week after the festival ended, young people from all over Germany were invited to write and play their own songs under the guidance of professional musicians. They were accommodated in the so-called Kuhle, the site of the first Wacken Open Air.\n\n=== Blood donations ===\nThe organisers regularly call for [[blood donation]]s with the whole festival team. Blood is donated at the Itzehoe Clinic and the entire wing is decorated in W:O:A style, while Heavy Metal is blasted through the speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shz.de/lokales/norddeutsche-rundschau/wacken-metal-fans-lassen-sich-anzapfen-id6834671.html|title=Wacken: Metal-Fans lassen sich anzapfen|last=|first=|date=14 June 2014|website=shz.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== DKMS typing campaign ===\nSince W:O:A 2014, visitors and musicians have been encouraged to have their [[bone marrow]] typed for donation by the [[DKMS|German Bone Marrow Donor Database]]. In 2014, 2,700 visitors took this opportunity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120607/http://www.dkms.de/de/content/wacken-und-die-dkms-%E2%80%93-laut-und-erfolgreich|title=Wacken und die DKMS \u2013 Laut und erfolgreich|last=|first=|date=|website=DKMS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Stark gegen Krebs \u2013 Strong against cancer ===\nThe festival works with the organisers of the so-called Wattol\u00fcmpiade (\"mudflat Olympics\") in [[Brunsb\u00fcttel]] to promote the slogan Stark gegen Krebs (\"Strong against cancer\"). The festival's team helps out with logistics for the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken.com/de/woa2015/main-news/news/archiv/archiv-single/article/stark-gegen-krebs-kooperation-vom-wacken-open-air-mit-der-wattoluempiade-9322/|title=Stark gegen Krebs|last=|first=|date=|website=wacken.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Network \u2013 W:O:A as a brand ==\n[[File:Wacken 2011 Impression 08.JPG|thumb|Tower with Wacken symbol, Wacken Open Air 2011]]\nIn addition to the festival itself, there are numerous other events planned and carried out by the organisers. A wide range of [[merchandising]] has also been developed over the years. In addition to T-shirts and a comprehensive range of CDs and DVDs, the festival also has accompanying [[print media]]. The ''W:O:A History Book'' contains the open-air\u2019s history up until 2005. The book Die Wahrheit \u00fcber Wacken (\"The truth about Wacken\", Oidium Verlag 2005, new edition published at Verlag Andreas Reiffer 2011) provides a more humorous account of the festival. It was written by satirist Till Burgw\u00e4chter in collaboration with comic artist Jan Oidium and is also available as an audio book comprising three CDs. The publication of a Metal cookbook shows how far merchandising has come. However, the mounting range of merchandising has led to growing criticism, as some consider it to be purely profit-oriented. The increasing coverage of the festival, especially in the wake of the documentary [[Full Metal Village]], is perceived by the traditional Metal scene as \"selling out\".\n\nIn 2005, Wacken Premium [[Pilsner]] was offered as the festival\u2019s \"own\" beer for the first time. It was produced in the Bavarian [[brewery]] Maximiliansbrauerei in [[Chieming]]. At W:O:A 2006 and 2007, the beer was available as well, this time produced in 0.5-litre bottles by the [[Flensburger Brauerei|Flensburger]] brewery. The large number of glass shards later forced the organisers to switch to 0.5-litre cans.\n\nAs a [[motto]], the phrase \"See you in Wacken - Rain or Shine\" has established itself alongside \"Faster, Harder, Louder\". Additionally, the festival features the sentence \"Louder Than Hell\" in its advertising.\n\n=== Full Metal Cruise ===\n[[Cruise ship|Cruises]] with Heavy Metal bands on board under the name [[Full Metal Cruise]] have been organised within Europe since 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamburg.de/kreuzfahrtschiffe/3500106/full-metal-cruise/|title=Full Metal Cruise: Heavy Metal auf hoher See|last=|first=|date=|website=Hamburg.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Hamburg Metal Dayz ===\nThe indoor festival [[Hamburg Metal Dayz]] takes place at the same time as the [[Reeperbahn]]-Festival and is considered a get-together for the scene. In addition to concerts, there are panels with musicians, managers, and other Metal experts, as well as workshops and a question and answer session with the W:O:A organisers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hh-mittendrin.de/2014/09/hamburg-metal-dayz-gepflegter-krach-in-der-markthalle/|title=Hamburg Metal Dayz \u2013 gepflegter Krach in der Markthalle|last=|first=|date=23 September 2014|website=hh-mittendrin.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Roadshow ===\n[[File:Grailknights \u2013 Wacken Roadshow 2014 01.jpg|thumb|[[Grailknights]] at Wacken Roadshow 2014]]\nFor the Wacken Roadshow, several bands tour Europe under the banner of Wacken Open Air. These concerts are meant to complement the warm-up parties organised in many places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-hammer.de/metal-hammer-praesentiert-woa-roadshow-2014-398382/|title=METAL HAMMER pr\u00e4sentiert: W:O:A Roadshow 2014|last=|first=|date=9 April 2014|website=Metal Hammer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Metal Monday ===\nIn the summer of 1990, Metal Monday took place for the first time at Knust in [[Hamburg]]. For five years, regional, national and international Metal bands like De la Cruz, 5th Avenue, and King K\u00f8ng played at Knust every Monday. After a break of almost 20 years, Metal Monday was revived by the Wacken Open Air organisers in 2014 in cooperation with the Knust, Seaside Touring, All Access, and Hamburg Konzerte. Metal, Rock, and Folkrock bands now perform once a month, following the motto \"three bands - small entrance fee\". In addition to regional bands, international newcomers are always invited.\n\n=== Zum Wackinger ===\n[[File:Martin Semmelrogge - Zum Wackinger - Wacken Winter Nights 2017 08.jpg|thumb|Reading with [[Martin Semmelrogge]] at Zum Wackinger 2017]]\nThe former country-style restaurant ''Zur Post'' in Wacken, built in 1919, has been the hub of the village and the surrounding communities for decades. It was here that bartenders Thomas Jensen and Holger H\u00fcbner conceived the idea for today's Wacken Open Air. Today, it is used to accommodate staff and to serve other business purposes. A series of events called \"Zum Wackinger\" sees artists from music, comedy, and entertainment perform regularly. Since 2016, a two-day medieval feast with jugglers and bards takes place here.<ref>press kit ICS Network, ''Zum Wackinger'', September 2016 (p. 37)</ref>\n\n=== Metal Church ===\nThe Evangelical Lutheran Village Church in Wacken belongs to the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] congregation of the [[Evangelical Church in Germany|Evangelical Lutheran Church]] in [[Northern Germany]]. For Wacken Open Air and Wacken Winter Nights, it is turned into the ''Metal Church''. During said festivals, the ''Metal Service'' is held here and bands from the Folk and Medieval scene perform in the church.\n\n=== Wacken Winter Nights ===\n[[File:Dunkelsch\u00f6n - Metal Church - Wacken Winter Nights 2017 01.jpg|thumb|[[Dunkelsch\u00f6n]] at Metal Church during Wacken Winter Nights]]\nWacken Winter Nights (WWN), a three-day Folk and Medieval open-air festival, took place for the first time in February 2017 at temperatures of -2 to -6 degrees Celsius in Wacken. With over 3,500 attendees, the festival's first edition sold out several weeks in advance. Most of them spent the nights on the camping site. A second edition took place from 23 to 25 February 2018. Due to the construction on the previous year's campground, the overnight accommodations were relocated to the area that is also used for the regular Open Air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/wwn-2018-festival-abc-und-plaene-verfuegbar/|title=WWN 2018 Festival ABC und Pl\u00e4ne verf\u00fcgbar!|last=|first=|date=2 February 2018|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The walking distance, therefore, increased to about 15 minutes. With 4,000 visitors, the 2018 event also sold out.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/ein-maerchen-aus-eis-und-feuer-die-wacken-winter-nights-2018-gehen-zu-ende/|title=Ein M\u00e4rchen aus Eis und Feuer \u2013 Die Wacken Winter Nights 2018 gehen zu Ende!|last=|first=|date=25 February 2018|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> For the third event in 2019, the festival grounds were expanded considerably and 5,000 visitors attended. The fourth WWNs are planned for the 14th to 16 February 2020.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wacken-winter-nights.com/neuigkeiten-mehr/news/news-detail/die-wacken-winter-nights-2019-gehen-zu-ende/|title=Die Wacken Winter Nights 2019 gehen zu Ende!|last=|first=|date=24 February 2019|website=wacken-winter-nights.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Bands\n!Paying \nattendees\n!Price (EUR)\n!Sold out\n|-\n|2017\n|\n|3500\n|69,00\n|yes\n|-\n|2018\n|35\n|4000<ref name=\":8\" />\n|\n|yes\n|-\n|2019\n|34\n|5000<ref name=\":9\" />\n|89,99\n|\n|}\n\n=== StrongmanRun ===\nThe [[Fisherman's Friend StrongmanRun]] visited the Metal festival grounds of Wacken for the first time in April 2016. With their Wacken debut, the StrongmanRun season formally kicked off. About 3,000 participants, some in colourful costumes, took part in the run on the 20&nbsp;km track with 40 obstacles. In 2017, the StrongmanRun took place on the festival grounds.<ref>press kit ICS Network, ''Fisherman\u2019s Friend StrongmanRun Goes Heavy In Wacken'', September 2016 (p. 36)</ref>\n\n=== Wacken Rocks ===\nSeveral open-air festivals called Wacken Rocks were held in the past to transport the Wacken atmosphere to other places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bild.de/regional/hannover/festival-wacken-rocks-seaside-beginnt-in-9517326.bild.html|title=Festival \"Wacken rocks Seaside\" beginnt in Aurich|last=|first=|date=25 August 2009|website=BILD.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Full Metal Mountain ===\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde - Wacken Open Air 2016 51.jpg|thumb|Snowcat used as an advertising medium for Full Metal Mountain 2017]]\nDuring the winters of 2016, 2017 and 2018, an annual ski trip to [[Nassfeld]], Austria was organised for Metal fans under the name ''Full Metal Mountain''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.full-metal-mountain.com/de/news/news/news-detail/full-metal-mountain-das-datum-steht/|title=Full Metal Mountain \u2013 das Datum steht!|last=|first=|date=17 March 2015|website=full-metal-mountain.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Numerous bands and artists were present. For 2019, the festival was cancelled entirely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockmagazine.net/full-metal-mountain-2019-abgesagt/|title=Full Metal Mountain 2019 abgesagt\u2026|last=|first=|date=3 October 2018|website=Rockmagazine.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Full Metal Holiday ===\nPlanning and preparation are underway for a holiday trip to [[Mallorca]] with the title ''Full Metal Holiday - Destination Mallorca'', which will offer Metal concerts on the beach from 12 to 19 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.full-metal-holiday.com/de/|title=Full Metal Holiday|last=|first=|date=|website=full-metal-holiday.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The event was originally planned for 2017 and said to head to Ibiza, then rescheduled for 2018 and changed to Mallorca.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mallorcamagazin.com/nachrichten/gesellschaft/2017/10/12/58355/heavy-metal-reise-nach-mallorca-auf-2018-verschoben.html|title=Heavy-Metal-Reise nach Mallorca auf 2018 verschoben|last=|first=|date=12 October 2017|website=mallorcamagazin.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== W:O:A in numbers ==\nThe following chart shows the development of prices and visitor numbers of past festivals as published by the organisers. Prices refer to a 3-day ticket (incl. parking and camping) in pre-sale (without additional fees). \n{| class=\"wiki