t|31 January 2020\n{{WDL|60|33|11|16|for=128|against=79|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/india/india-fc-goa/31405/|title=FC Goa: Matches|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|409|164|102|143|for=546|against=522|diff=yes}}\n!\u2014\t\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Goa'''\n*[[Super Cup (India)]]: [[2019 Indian Super Cup|2019]]<ref name=SC/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol manager|500074}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Sergio Lobera \u2013 managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{UD Las Palmas managers}}\n{{Moghreb T\u00e9touan managers}}\n{{FC Goa managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lobera, Sergio}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Zaragoza]]\n[[Category:Aragonese sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:Terrassa FC managers]]\n[[Category:AD Ceuta managers]]\n[[Category:UD Las Palmas managers]]\n[[Category:Moghreb T\u00e9touan managers]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League head coaches]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in India]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n", "name_user": "CaxiasScream", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Lobera"}
{"title_page": "Donald Ramotar", "text_new": "{{short description|Guyanese politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|name          = Donald Ramotar\n|image         = Donald Ramotar.png\n|office        =8th [[President of Guyana]]\n|vicepresident = [[Sam Hinds]]\n|primeminister = [[Sam Hinds]]\n|term_start    = 3 December 2011\n|term_end      = 16 May 2015\n|predecessor   = [[Bharrat Jagdeo]]\n|successor     = [[David A. Granger|David Granger]]\n|spouse        = [[Deolatchmee Ramotar]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1950|10|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Caria Caria]], [[Guyana]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]]\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Guyana]]\n|religion = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n'''Donald Rabindranauth Ramotar''' (born 22 October 1950<ref>[http://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2011/04/05/ramotar-gets-unanimous-selection-as-ppp-presidential-candidate/ \"Ramotar gets unanimous selection as PPP Presidential Candidate\"], ''Kaieteur News'', 5 April 2011.</ref>) is a [[Guyana|Guyanese]] politician who was [[President of Guyana]] from 2011 to 2015. He was also the General Secretary of the [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]] (PPP) from 1997 to 2013.\n\n==Political career==\nRamotar joined the PPP in 1967 and was first elected to the PPP Central Committee in 1979; he joined the PPP Executive Committee in 1983. He received a certificate from the Government Technical Institute (GTI) in welding. From 1988 to 1993, he was International Secretary of the [[Guyana Agricultural Workers' Union]]. In the [[1992 Guyanese general election|1992 election]], in which the PPP under [[Cheddi Jagan]] won power for first time in decades, Ramotar was elected to the [[National Assembly of Guyana]]; he was continuously re-elected thereafter. He was designated as the PPP's Executive Secretary in 1993.<ref name=Isles>Kwesi Isles, [http://www.demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2896:pppcs-ramotar-declared-guyanas-president&catid=1 \"PPP/C's Ramotar declared Guyana's new president\"], ''Demerara Waves'', 1 December 2011.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203180654/http://www.demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2896%3Apppcs-ramotar-declared-guyanas-president&catid=1 |date=3 December 2011 }}</ref>  Following Jagan's death in March 1997, Ramotar was unanimously elected to succeed him as the PPP's General Secretary on March 29, 1997.<ref>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/history/historyppp.htm \"History of PPP\"], PPP website.</ref>\n\nAt the PPP's 29th Congress, he was re-elected to its Central Committee on August 2, 2008, receiving the fourth-highest number of votes (637).<ref>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/releases/The%20People%20Progressive%20Party%20PPP%20at%20its%2029%20th%20Congress.html Press release on Central Committee election], August 3, 2008.</ref><ref name=GT>[http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/news/news/84-news/412-donald-ramotar-re-elected-general-secretary-of-ppp.html \"Donald Ramotar re-elected General Secretary of PPP\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820230348/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/news/news/84-news/412-donald-ramotar-re-elected-general-secretary-of-ppp.html |date=August 20, 2008 }}, ''Guyana Times'', August 13, 2008.</ref> Following the Congress, he was re-elected by the Central Committee as General Secretary on August 12, 2008, without opposition;<ref name=GT/><ref name=EC>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/releases/PPP%20GENERAL%20SECRETARY%20EXECUTIVE%20COMMITTEE%20ELECTED.html \"PPP General Secretary, Executive Committee elected\"], PPP press statement, August 12, 2008.</ref> he was also elected to the editorial board of the PPP paper ''Thunder'' on this occasion.<ref name=EC/>\n\nOn 4 April 2011, the PPP Central Committee chose Ramotar as the party's presidential candidate for the [[2011 Guyanese general election|November 2011 election]]. The decision was unanimous; the other candidates withdrew and thereby obviated the need for a vote by secret ballot.<ref>[http://www.guyanapress.com/archives/6193 \"Presidential favourite Donald Ramotar wins candidacy to lead the PPP/C in the 2011 elections\"]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The Guyana Press'', 4 April 2011.</ref> The government announced on 28 April 2011 that Ramotar had been appointed to the post of Political Adviser to President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]]; previously Ramotar had held no official position in the administration. The opposition criticized the appointment; it argued that the government was merely reacting to criticism that it effectively sponsored Ramotar's candidacy by including him on official trips, and therefore, was giving him an official job in order to legitimize the situation. The government argued that Ramotar's inclusion on official trips was acceptable because the government was implementing the policies of the ruling party, led by Ramotar.<ref>[http://demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1618:dr-doobay-not-being-treated-as-a-suspect-in-wifes-murder-lawyer&catid=14&Itemid=122 \"Ramotar's presidential advisor appointment is back-door campaign financing - opposition\"], ''Demerara Waves'', 28 April 2011.</ref>\n\nThe election was held on 28 November 2011, and he was declared the winner when results were announced on 1 December. However, the PPP fell one seat short of a parliamentary majority, winning 32 out of 65 seats, meaning that Ramotar would serve as President while two opposition parties would together hold a majority of seats in the National Assembly.<ref name=Isles/><ref name=Wins>Denis Chabrol, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gBrx0ANfJdmz17g4TfNwTzuXmkKw?docId=CNG.6b9bdfd8a7780dfe67a072dc90f22150.d1 \"Ethnic Indian candidate wins presidency in Guyana\"], [[Agence France-Presse]], 1 December 2011.</ref> Ramotar expressed disappointment with his party's failure to win a majority, but he said that \"the electorate has spoken and we have to work with what we have\".<ref name=Wins/> He was sworn in as President on 3 December 2011.<ref>[http://www.stabroeknews.com/2011/news/stories/12/03/ramotar-sworn-in-as-seventh-executive-president/ \"Ramotar sworn in as seventh Executive President\"], ''[[Stabroek News]]'', 3 December 2011.</ref>\n\nDuring his first two years as President, Ramotar remained in his post as General Secretary of the PPP, but eventually he stepped aside from the party leadership, citing the heavy workload. The PPP Central Committee elected [[Clement Rohee]] to succeed Ramotar as General Secretary on 19 August 2013; Ramotar nominated Rohee for the post.<ref>[http://www.inewsguyana.com/breaking-news-clement-rohee-elected-as-new-general-secretary-of-ppp/ \"Clement Rohee elected as new General Secretary of PPP\"], INEWS Guyana, 19 August 2013.</ref>\n\nRamotar, said that [[Bashar al-Assad]] win in the [[2014 Syrian presidential election]] is a great victory for Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sana.sy/eng/21/2014/06/21/551372.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140621123014/http://sana.sy/eng/21/2014/06/21/551372.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 June 2014|title=\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0628\u0627\u0621 - Syrian Arab News Agency|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nDonald Ramotar and the PPP lost the [[2015 Guyanese general election|11 May 2015 general election]] to the opposition [[A Partnership for National Unity|APNU]] \u2013 [[Alliance for Change (Guyana)|AFC]] coalition led by [[David A. Granger]], which won by a slim margin.<ref>\n[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-32747514 \"Ex-general David Granger wins Guyana election\"], BBC News, 15 May 2015.</ref> President Ramotar left office on 16 May 2015, when Granger was sworn in.<ref>[http://newsnow.gy/politics/granger-sworn-in-as-president/ \"Granger sworn in as President\"], Newsnow Guyana, 16 May 2015.</ref> Ramotar was not included in the list of the PPP's 32 MPs in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.stabroeknews.com/2015/news/stories/07/07/jagdeo-on-pppc-parliament-list/ \"Jagdeo on PPP/C Parliament list\"], ''Stabroek News'', 7 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year!! Country!! Award Name!! Given by!! Field of Merit\n|-\n|2015||{{GUY}}||[[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]||[[President of India]]||Public affairs\n|-\n|}\n\nHe was awarded the ''[[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]'' by [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Narendra Modi]] at the annual [[Pravasi Bharatiya Divas]] of January 2015 held in [[Gandhinagar]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|title=President Ramotar to receive Pravasi Bharatiya Samman award|url=http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/2015/01/07/president-ramotar-to-receive-pravasi-bharatiya-samman-award/|accessdate=3 May 2015|work=Guyana Times|date=7 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518104245/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/2015/01/07/president-ramotar-to-receive-pravasi-bharatiya-samman-award/|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111121011945/http://www.op.gov.gy/ Office of the President of Guyana]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bharrat Jagdeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Guyana]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David A. Granger|David Granger]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Heads of State of Guyana}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramotar, Donald}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Guyana)]]\n[[Category:People's Progressive Party (Guyana) politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Guyana]]\n[[Category:University of Guyana alumni]]\n[[Category:Guyanese politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Guyanese Hindus]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Guyanese politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|name          = Donald Ramotar\n|native_name = \u0921\u094b\u0928\u093e\u0932\u094d\u0921 \u0930\u092c\u0940\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930\u0928\u093e\u0925 \u0930\u093e\u092e\u094b\u091f\u0930\n|image         = Donald Ramotar.png\n|office        =8th [[President of Guyana]]\n|vicepresident = [[Sam Hinds]]\n|primeminister = [[Sam Hinds]]\n|term_start    = 3 December 2011\n|term_end      = 16 May 2015\n|predecessor   = [[Bharrat Jagdeo]]\n|successor     = [[David A. Granger|David Granger]]\n|spouse        = [[Deolatchmee Ramotar]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1950|10|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Caria Caria]], [[Guyana]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]]\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Guyana]]\n|religion = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n'''Donald Rabindranauth Ramotar''' (born 22 October 1950<ref>[http://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2011/04/05/ramotar-gets-unanimous-selection-as-ppp-presidential-candidate/ \"Ramotar gets unanimous selection as PPP Presidential Candidate\"], ''Kaieteur News'', 5 April 2011.</ref>) is a [[Guyana|Guyanese]] politician who was [[President of Guyana]] from 2011 to 2015. He was also the General Secretary of the [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]] (PPP) from 1997 to 2013.\n\n==Political career==\nRamotar joined the PPP in 1967 and was first elected to the PPP Central Committee in 1979; he joined the PPP Executive Committee in 1983. He received a certificate from the Government Technical Institute (GTI) in welding. From 1988 to 1993, he was International Secretary of the [[Guyana Agricultural Workers' Union]]. In the [[1992 Guyanese general election|1992 election]], in which the PPP under [[Cheddi Jagan]] won power for first time in decades, Ramotar was elected to the [[National Assembly of Guyana]]; he was continuously re-elected thereafter. He was designated as the PPP's Executive Secretary in 1993.<ref name=Isles>Kwesi Isles, [http://www.demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2896:pppcs-ramotar-declared-guyanas-president&catid=1 \"PPP/C's Ramotar declared Guyana's new president\"], ''Demerara Waves'', 1 December 2011.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203180654/http://www.demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2896%3Apppcs-ramotar-declared-guyanas-president&catid=1 |date=3 December 2011 }}</ref>  Following Jagan's death in March 1997, Ramotar was unanimously elected to succeed him as the PPP's General Secretary on March 29, 1997.<ref>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/history/historyppp.htm \"History of PPP\"], PPP website.</ref>\n\nAt the PPP's 29th Congress, he was re-elected to its Central Committee on August 2, 2008, receiving the fourth-highest number of votes (637).<ref>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/releases/The%20People%20Progressive%20Party%20PPP%20at%20its%2029%20th%20Congress.html Press release on Central Committee election], August 3, 2008.</ref><ref name=GT>[http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/news/news/84-news/412-donald-ramotar-re-elected-general-secretary-of-ppp.html \"Donald Ramotar re-elected General Secretary of PPP\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820230348/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/news/news/84-news/412-donald-ramotar-re-elected-general-secretary-of-ppp.html |date=August 20, 2008 }}, ''Guyana Times'', August 13, 2008.</ref> Following the Congress, he was re-elected by the Central Committee as General Secretary on August 12, 2008, without opposition;<ref name=GT/><ref name=EC>[http://www.ppp-civic.org/releases/PPP%20GENERAL%20SECRETARY%20EXECUTIVE%20COMMITTEE%20ELECTED.html \"PPP General Secretary, Executive Committee elected\"], PPP press statement, August 12, 2008.</ref> he was also elected to the editorial board of the PPP paper ''Thunder'' on this occasion.<ref name=EC/>\n\nOn 4 April 2011, the PPP Central Committee chose Ramotar as the party's presidential candidate for the [[2011 Guyanese general election|November 2011 election]]. The decision was unanimous; the other candidates withdrew and thereby obviated the need for a vote by secret ballot.<ref>[http://www.guyanapress.com/archives/6193 \"Presidential favourite Donald Ramotar wins candidacy to lead the PPP/C in the 2011 elections\"]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The Guyana Press'', 4 April 2011.</ref> The government announced on 28 April 2011 that Ramotar had been appointed to the post of Political Adviser to President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]]; previously Ramotar had held no official position in the administration. The opposition criticized the appointment; it argued that the government was merely reacting to criticism that it effectively sponsored Ramotar's candidacy by including him on official trips, and therefore, was giving him an official job in order to legitimize the situation. The government argued that Ramotar's inclusion on official trips was acceptable because the government was implementing the policies of the ruling party, led by Ramotar.<ref>[http://demerarawaves.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1618:dr-doobay-not-being-treated-as-a-suspect-in-wifes-murder-lawyer&catid=14&Itemid=122 \"Ramotar's presidential advisor appointment is back-door campaign financing - opposition\"], ''Demerara Waves'', 28 April 2011.</ref>\n\nThe election was held on 28 November 2011, and he was declared the winner when results were announced on 1 December. However, the PPP fell one seat short of a parliamentary majority, winning 32 out of 65 seats, meaning that Ramotar would serve as President while two opposition parties would together hold a majority of seats in the National Assembly.<ref name=Isles/><ref name=Wins>Denis Chabrol, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gBrx0ANfJdmz17g4TfNwTzuXmkKw?docId=CNG.6b9bdfd8a7780dfe67a072dc90f22150.d1 \"Ethnic Indian candidate wins presidency in Guyana\"], [[Agence France-Presse]], 1 December 2011.</ref> Ramotar expressed disappointment with his party's failure to win a majority, but he said that \"the electorate has spoken and we have to work with what we have\".<ref name=Wins/> He was sworn in as President on 3 December 2011.<ref>[http://www.stabroeknews.com/2011/news/stories/12/03/ramotar-sworn-in-as-seventh-executive-president/ \"Ramotar sworn in as seventh Executive President\"], ''[[Stabroek News]]'', 3 December 2011.</ref>\n\nDuring his first two years as President, Ramotar remained in his post as General Secretary of the PPP, but eventually he stepped aside from the party leadership, citing the heavy workload. The PPP Central Committee elected [[Clement Rohee]] to succeed Ramotar as General Secretary on 19 August 2013; Ramotar nominated Rohee for the post.<ref>[http://www.inewsguyana.com/breaking-news-clement-rohee-elected-as-new-general-secretary-of-ppp/ \"Clement Rohee elected as new General Secretary of PPP\"], INEWS Guyana, 19 August 2013.</ref>\n\nRamotar, said that [[Bashar al-Assad]] win in the [[2014 Syrian presidential election]] is a great victory for Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sana.sy/eng/21/2014/06/21/551372.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140621123014/http://sana.sy/eng/21/2014/06/21/551372.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 June 2014|title=\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0628\u0627\u0621 - Syrian Arab News Agency|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nDonald Ramotar and the PPP lost the [[2015 Guyanese general election|11 May 2015 general election]] to the opposition [[A Partnership for National Unity|APNU]] \u2013 [[Alliance for Change (Guyana)|AFC]] coalition led by [[David A. Granger]], which won by a slim margin.<ref>\n[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-32747514 \"Ex-general David Granger wins Guyana election\"], BBC News, 15 May 2015.</ref> President Ramotar left office on 16 May 2015, when Granger was sworn in.<ref>[http://newsnow.gy/politics/granger-sworn-in-as-president/ \"Granger sworn in as President\"], Newsnow Guyana, 16 May 2015.</ref> Ramotar was not included in the list of the PPP's 32 MPs in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.stabroeknews.com/2015/news/stories/07/07/jagdeo-on-pppc-parliament-list/ \"Jagdeo on PPP/C Parliament list\"], ''Stabroek News'', 7 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year!! Country!! Award Name!! Given by!! Field of Merit\n|-\n|2015||{{GUY}}||[[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]||[[President of India]]||Public affairs\n|-\n|}\n\nHe was awarded the ''[[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]'' by [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Narendra Modi]] at the annual [[Pravasi Bharatiya Divas]] of January 2015 held in [[Gandhinagar]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|title=President Ramotar to receive Pravasi Bharatiya Samman award|url=http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/2015/01/07/president-ramotar-to-receive-pravasi-bharatiya-samman-award/|accessdate=3 May 2015|work=Guyana Times|date=7 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518104245/http://www.guyanatimesgy.com/2015/01/07/president-ramotar-to-receive-pravasi-bharatiya-samman-award/|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111121011945/http://www.op.gov.gy/ Office of the President of Guyana]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bharrat Jagdeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Guyana]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David A. Granger|David Granger]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Heads of State of Guyana}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramotar, Donald}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Guyana)]]\n[[Category:People's Progressive Party (Guyana) politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Guyana]]\n[[Category:University of Guyana alumni]]\n[[Category:Guyanese politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Guyanese Hindus]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]\n", "name_user": "BaronJaguar", "label": "safe", "comment": "there is no 'native name' in indian script.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Ramotar"}
{"title_page": "Trefl Gda\u0144sk", "text_new": "{{Infobox volleyball club\n| clubname    = Trefl Gda\u0144sk \n| short name  = \n| nickname    = \n| image       = [[File:TreflGdansk Logo.png|200px]] \n| fullname    = Trefl Gda\u0144sk Sp\u00f3\u0142ka Akcyjna\n| founded     = 2005\n| dissolved   = \n| ground      = [[Ergo Arena]]<br />Plac Dw\u00f3ch Miast 1<br />[[Gda\u0144sk]]\n| capacity    = 11,200\n| chairman    = {{flagicon|POL}} Dariusz Gadomski\n| manager     = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Micha\u0142 Winiarski]]\n| captain     = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Wojciech Grzyb]]\n| league      = [[PlusLiga]]\n| season      = \n| position    = \n| website     = https://treflgdansk.pl/\n| pattern_la1 = _borderonwhite\n| pattern_b1  = _whitecollar\n| pattern_ra1 = _borderonwhite\n| pattern_s1  = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| pattern_la2 = _blackborder\n| pattern_b2  = _blackcollar\n| pattern_ra2 = _blackborder\n| pattern_s2  = \n| leftarm2    = 000000\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = 000000\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| current     =\n}}\n\n'''Trefl Gda\u0144sk''' is a [[Poland|Polish]] [[volleyball]] team based in [[Gda\u0144sk]]. In 2008 the club debuted in the highest level Polish volleyball men's league, [[PlusLiga]]. In the seasons 2009/2010 and 2010/2011 the club played in the first league, and in 2011 they returned to [[PlusLiga]].<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Jeste%C5%9Bmy+w+PlusLidze!+Lotos+Trefl+Gda%C5%84sk+-+Jadar+Radom+3%3A0&news_id=9474&extra-param=1 ''Jeste\u015bmy w PlusLidze! Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk - Jadar Radom 3:0''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 01-05-2011</ref> Their home matches are being played at the [[Ergo Arena]].\n\n==Achievements==\n* [[PlusLiga|Polish Championship]]\n*: [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]\n*: [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' [[2017\u201318 PlusLiga|2018]]\n* [[Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]]\n*: [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] '''(x2)''' [[2014\u201315 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|2015]], [[2017\u201318 Polish Cup of men's volleyball|2018]]\n* Polish SuperCup\n*: [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 2015\n\n[[File:Lotos Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (6203615850).jpg|thumb|The team during match with [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w|PGE Skra]] on 30 September 2011.]]\n[[File:Lotos Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (6203123879).jpg|thumb|The team during match with [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w|PGE Skra]] on 30 September 2011.]]\n[[File:LOTOS Trefl Gda\u0144sk - ZAKSA K\u0119dzierzyn-Ko\u017ale (8087192276).jpg|thumb|Warm-up before a match with [[ZAKSA K\u0119dzierzyn-Ko\u017ale]] on 14 October 2012.]]\n[[File:LOTOS Trefl Gda\u0144sk vs Indykpol AZS Olsztyn (8217475189).jpg|thumb|Middle-blocker during his attack in match against [[Indykpol AZS Olsztyn]] on 23 November 2012.]]\n[[File:Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (8580202834).jpg|thumb|[[Grzegorz \u0141omacz]] as a setter in match against [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] in 2013.]]\n[[File:Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (8580187830).jpg|thumb|A middle-blocker [[Daniel Pli\u0144ski]] (#4) and setter [[Grzegorz \u0141omacz]] (#3) in match [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] vs '''Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk''' in 2013.]]\n[[File:Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (8579113259).jpg|thumb|'''Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk''' vs [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] on 17 March 2013.]]\n[[File:Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk vs Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w (8580185916).jpg|thumb|A match '''Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk''' vs [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] in season 2012/2013.]]\n\n==History==\nIn the 2013/2014 season, LOTOS Trefl coach was [[Rados\u0142aw Panas]].<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Rados%C5%82aw+Panas+odchodzi+z+LOTOSU+Trefla&news_id=14604&extra-param=1 ''Rados\u0142aw Panas odchodzi z LOTOSU Trefla''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 09-04-2014</ref> During his work as a main coach the team won 9 times and lost 11 matches. The club didn't play in the [[PlusLiga]] play-offs and ended the season 2013/2014 on 10th place.<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=LOTOS+Trefl+efektownie+zamkn%C4%85%C5%82+sezon&news_id=14577&extra-param=1 ''LOTOS Trefl efektownie zamkn\u0105\u0142 sezon''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 05-04-2014</ref> In June 2014, the Italian [[Andrea Anastasi]] was officially presented as the club's new coach.<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Andrea+Anastasi+trenerem+LOTOSU+Trefla+Gda%C5%84sk&news_id=14901&extra-param=1 ''Andrea Anastasi trenerem LOTOSU Trefla Gda\u0144sk''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 05-06-2014</ref><ref>[http://www.plusliga.pl/news/id/9291 ''Andrea Anastasi trenerem LOTOSU Trefla Gda\u0144sk''] \u2013 plusliga.pl \u2013 05-06-2014</ref> Anastasi was a head coach of the [[Poland men's national volleyball team|Polish national team]] in 2011-2013 and expressed a desire to work for the club from Gda\u0144sk. New players [[Damian Schulz]]<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Damian+Schulz+graczem+LOTOSU+Trefla&news_id=14925&extra-param=1 ''Damian Schulz graczem LOTOSU Trefla''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 11-06-2014</ref>, [[Mateusz Mika]]<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Mateusz+Mika+wraca+do+Gda%C5%84ska&news_id=14954&extra-param=1 ''Mateusz Mika wraca do Gda\u0144ska''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 18-06-2014</ref>, [[Wojciech Grzyb]] signed a contract with the club before 2014/2015 season.<ref>[http://www.sport.trefl.com/siatkowka/aktualnosci/?title=Wojciech+Grzyb+wzmacnia+gda%C5%84ski+blok&news_id=14974&extra-param=1 ''Wojciech Grzyb wzmacnia gda\u0144ski blok''] \u2013 sport.trefl.com \u2013 24-06-2014</ref> Team took 3rd place in regular season of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|PlusLiga]]. [[Andrea Anastasi|Anastasi]]'s team won 19 and lost 7 matches. On 23 February 2015 [[Andrea Anastasi]] signed new two-years contract, because of good results in regular season till 2017.<ref>[http://www.plusliga.pl/news/id/10786 ''Andrea Anastasi poprowadzi LOTOS Trefl przez kolejne dwa lata''] \u2013 plusliga.pl \u2013 23-02-2015</ref> LOTOS Trefl advanced to the final of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga]] after winning in semifinal against Polish Champion [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] (in the competition to three wins, result was 3-1). It was the first, historical promotion to the final of Polish Championship.<ref>[http://www.sportowefakty.pl/siatkowka/512424/piekny-sen-gdanszczan-trwa-belchatowianie-nie-obronia-tytulu-relacja-z-meczu-lot ''Pi\u0119kny sen gda\u0144szczan trwa! Be\u0142chatowianie nie obroni\u0105 tytu\u0142u - relacja z meczu Lotos Trefl Gda\u0144sk - PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w''] \u2013 sportowefakty.pl \u2013 04-04-2015</ref>\n\n==Former names==\n{|\n|-\n| '''2005\u20132007''' || ''Trefl Gda\u0144sk''\n|-\n| '''2007\u20132008''' || ''Trefl Pi\u0142ka Siatkowa SA Gda\u0144sk''\n|-\n| '''2008\u20132011''' || ''Trefl Gda\u0144sk''\n|-\n| '''2011\u20132017''' || ''LOTOS Trefl Gda\u0144sk''\n|-\n| '''2017\u2013present''' || ''Trefl Gda\u0144sk''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Coaches==\n{|\n|-\n| '''2005\u20132006''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Antoni Perzyna \n|-\n| '''2006\u20132007''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Rafa\u0142 Prus\n|-\n| '''2007\u20132009''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Wojciech Kasza\n|-\n| '''2009\u20132010''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Jerzy Strumi\u0142\u0142o\n|-\n| '''2010\u20132011''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Dariusz Luks\n|-\n| '''2011''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Grzegorz Ry\u015b\n|-\n| '''2011\u20132013''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Dariusz Luks\n|-\n| '''2013\u20132014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Rados\u0142aw Panas]]\n|-\n| '''2014\u20132019''' || {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Andrea Anastasi]]\n|-\n| '''2019\u2013''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Micha\u0142 Winiarski]]\n|}\n\n==Team==\n{{main article|Trefl Gda\u0144sk squads}}\n\n===2020/